{The introductory moves of the Tartakower-Makogonov-Bondarevsky variation, one
of the World Champions' Boris Spassky and Anatoly Karpov favourite weapons,
are:} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {
[#] About a century ago, Rudolf Spielmann explained the essence of Black's
opening problems after 1.d4: He can develop one of his bishops easily but will
face bigger problems to do the same with his colleague. In the Queen's Gambit
Declined, 2...e6 opens the diagonal for the king's bishop but obstructs the
h3-c8 diagonal. The classical solution used to be preparing ...dxc4 followed
by a queenside expansion after which the queen's bishop could finally develop
to b7. But this approach implies staying underdeveloped for several moves,
with the respective risk that Black would not manage to develop properly at
all. The last move offers a quicker solution to the problem, as Black will
play ...Bb7 next. This is a double-edged decision as Black now gets some
weaknesses on the light squares. But many decades of practice have proved that
the hanging pawns created by a later ...c7-c5, followed by exchanges on d5 and
c5, have enough dynamic potential to compensate for their relative static
weakness. As a historical overview, the last move was played for the first time
by Shovalter in 1915, but then Tartakower played it regularly starting with
1922 until the late '30s. Later, it became part of Makogonov's and, more
notably, Bondarevsky's repertoire. The latter then passed it to Boris Spassky,
who was his pupil during the ascension to the World crown. The way I see the
theory of this system, it is essential to know a series of typical structures
and choose between them according to the concrete circumstances. Below I have
picked up a few quiet lines illustrating the most important structures and the
way they can be reached.} 8. Be2 {The most neutral move.} (8. cxd5 {is
supposed to be pleasant for White after 8...cxd5, but I have obtained good
results with black with this line, true, coming from a different move order (4.
..Nbd7 and only later ...b7-b6). But with the given move order the position
arising after} Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 {is comfortable for
Black as he can use the early exchange to develop his bishop on a better
square than b7 with} Be6 {[#]We will call this structure A).}) (8. Bd3 {
looks more active than 8.Be2, but it releases the latent pressure on d5. The
difference can be felt after} Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c5 ({
This is possible precisely because Black does not face early problems along
the d-file. If Black plays the same as in the main line below,} 11... c6 {
White achieves e3-e4 quicker, maybe just now:} 12. e4) 12. Rc1 (12. dxc5 bxc5 {
[#]We have reached Structure B), the hanging pawns with the bishop pair for
Black.}) 12... Nd7 13. Bb1 Re8 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nd4 {This is not a typical
Isolani - C). [#] It may seem that Black is in a better situation than in the
standard Isolani structure because his bishop is apparently passive on b7. But
the fact is that the constant pressure exerted by the other bishop and the
activity of the knight face White with problems enjoying the blockade on d4.
At the first given possibility, the pawn could advance to d4, activating both
bishops.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This and the next move are a complement to many
moves (8.Qb3, 8.Qc2, 8.Rc1, for instance). After 8...Bb7 general exchanges on
d5 ending up with ...Bxd5 would solve Black's problems, so it makes sense to
eliminate the knight on f6.} ({Another typical structure with hanging pawns
but all bishops on board this time arises after} 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 c5 11.
cxd5 exd5 {[#]Structure D)}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Qb3 {The kind of move
aimed at inhibiting ...c7-c5.} (11. b4 {is even more direct.} c6 ({The line} 
11... c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Bb5 {used to be played a
lot in the Karpov-Kasparov matches. Black should be able to reach a draw with
accurate play, but I don't like the idea to start struggling so early.}) 12.
O-O Re8 13. Qb3 a5 14. b5 {The most principled answer.} c5 {This can again be
classified as Structure B)}) ({A more neutral setup is} 11. Rc1 Qe7 12. O-O Rd8
13. Qc2 Nd7 14. Rfd1 c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Nd4 {reaching structure C) above.})
11... c6 12. O-O Nd7 13. Rad1 Re8 {The start of a flexible regrouping. The
knight is heading for e6 in order to take control over c5 and d4.} 14. Rfe1
Nf8 15. e4 {There is little else White can undertake.} Ne6 $1 {Putting
pressure on d4 and inviting White to release the tension.} ({In all similar
cases, releasing the tension leaves White with pleasant play. But here,} 15...
dxe4 16. Bc4 Qc7 17. Nxe4 $14 {leads to a concrete advantage already.}) 16. e5
({Or if} 16. exd5 cxd5 {E)[#]The structure is symmetrical and all Black's
pieces are optimally placed. White could claim an advantage only if he could
install and consolidate the knight on e5, but this is rarely possible.
Therefore, I prefer this type of positions with black.}) 16... Be7 {[#]This is
my favourite structure in the Tartakower Universe - F). The knight on e6 is a
perfect blocker, ensuring the kingside's safety and allowing Black to generate
counterplay in the centre with ...c6-c5. Black could also open new horizons
for his dark-squared bishop with ...Bf8, ...g7-g6 and ...h6-h5. I will now
illustrate the main ideas of each structure mentioned above.} *

