{[#] This is one of the most favourable structures that Black can get in this
line. Black usually enjoys a comfortable play since his bishop is not stuck on
b7. In this position, Black's play is quite natural. If White makes slow moves,
Black will play ...c7-c5 followed by ...Nc6, ...Rfd8, and ...Rac8. After c7-c5,
White can always go for hanging pawns by playing dxc5 (Structure B). If White
refrains from dxc5, Black has two different plans. 1) Put pressure on d4 After
playing c7-c5, the possibility to put pressure on d4 is quite attractive.
Black can achieve it with simple moves such as ...Bg4, ...Qf6, and ...Nc6.2)
Go for a pawn expansion on the queenside Very often, Black starts rolling his
queenside pawns. The queenside play is quite natural - ...c5-c4 followed by
b6-b5-b4. Before going for such an expansion, Black should make sure that he
has a good development and strong control of the centre. Otherwise, White can
strike in the centre with e3-e4 or undermine the queenside structure with
b2-b3.}  *

