{Structure A)} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7.
Bh4 b6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3
Rc8 {The first impression is that Black faces slight problems. The c5-pawn is
pinned and, in the absence of the dark-squared bishop, a bit vulnerable. But
this famous game reveals the hidden dynamism of Black's position.} 14. Bb5 {
At first sight, a very logical move. The bishop dominates the knight as after.
.. Nd7, Bxd7 would really leave Black vulnerable on the dark squares. It had
been played for the first time in Furman, S-Geller, E Moscow 1970 (1-0, 32) and
then taken up by Fischer in Fischer, R-Spassky, B Reykjavik (m/6) 1972 (1-0, 41).
} Qb7 $1 {This strong novelty has a curious history.} ({Both aforementioned
games went} 14... a6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O Ra7 17. Be2 {leaving Black poorly
coordinated. During the 1972 match, rumours spread that Geller, who was
Spassky's main second had shown him the improvement 14...Qb7! during their
pre-match training camp. When working on his book on the match, Timman
analyzed this move, concluding that it was insufficient. One year later,
Geller himself had the occasion to prove him wrong. One of the main
ingredients of success when delivering a novelty is the surprise effect. If
the opponent knows your plans many months in advance, the boomerang effect may
occur. But Geller's understanding was by far deeper than that of one of the
most talented young grandmasters, even though the latter had a hint about it.})
15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rxc5 {Otherwise the bishop would be hanging, turning
Furman's novelty into a mere waste of time.} Rxc5 17. Qxc5 {[#]} Na6 $3 {
A brilliant, paradoxical and simple move at the same time. The exchange offered
by Black seems to leave White with a crushing advantage due to his
unchallenged control over d4. But on the other hand, the best way of fighting
for the initiative when having a lead in development is... developing!} ({
Timman only analyzed} 17... a6 18. Bd3 (18. Ba4 $1 $16 {keeping the knight
dominated is even stronger.}) 18... Qxb2 19. O-O Nd7 20. Qc6 Rb8 21. Nd4 {
rightly concluding that White should keep an advantage.}) 18. Bxa6 (18. Qc6
Qxc6 19. Bxc6 Rb8 $1 $15 {Black retrieves the pawn on b2, with strong
initiative ensured by his rook's activity on the second rank. The point is
that after} 20. b3 $2 Rc8 {White does not dispose over Ba4-d1 anymore, so
Black wins at least a piece, for instance} 21. Nd4 Nb4) 18... Qxa6 {The king
is arrested in the centre and White will play without his rook for quite a
while.} 19. Qa3 Qc4 {[#]} 20. Kd2 ({A difficult decision. If} 20. Qc3 Rb8 21.
Qxc4 dxc4 22. b3 cxb3 23. axb3 Rxb3 24. O-O a5 {the endgame is very dangerous
for White.}) 20... Qg4 $1 {White's lack of coordination starts telling.} 21.
Rg1 d4 $1 {Finally crushing White's hopes for a stable blockade.} 22. Nxd4 (22.
exd4 Rb8 $17 {would leave the king under an attack from all sides.}) 22... Qh4 23.
Re1 Qxf2+ ({Even more convincing seems} 23... Bc4 24. f3 Qxh2 $17) 24. Re2 Qf1
25. Nxe6 fxe6 26. Qd6 Kh8 $1 {[#]Indirectly defending the e6-pawn as White
cannot afford to allow ...Rd8+. Despite his extra pawn White is in big trouble.
In positions with queens and rooks, the king's safety is essential and White
does not stand well in regard to that.} 27. e4 Rc8 28. Ke3 Rf8 29. Rd2 e5 30.
Qxe5 $2 Qe1+ 31. Re2 Qg1+ 32. Kd3 Rd8+ 33. Kc3 Qd1 34. Qb5 Qd4+ 35. Kc2 a6 $1
36. Qxa6 Qc5+ 37. Kb3 Rb8+ 0-1

