{In the previous game, the break ... d5-d4 yielded Black a decisive advantage.
In the next example, the key move could have been ...c5-c4 had Black not
underestimated White's resources in the critical position.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10.
cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Qb3 Bc6 14. Be2 Nd7 15. Rfd1 Rb8 16. Qc2
Qa5 $15 {[#]A brief glance at the position is enough to reveal that things
have gone Black's way. The d5 pawn is indirectly defended due to the pressure
on b2 and Black queenside initiative is likely to become alarming soon.} 17.
Nd2 $5 {The best practical chance, threatening Nb3 followed by Nxd5. [#]} ({If
} 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Rxb2 19. Qd1 Nb6 20. Rd6 {(The only move, aiming to
answer 20...Rxe2 with 21.Rxf6).} c4 $17) 17... Rxb2 $6 {After this tempting
but premature combination White is very much back into the game.} (17... c4 $1
$17 {would have prevented Nb3 and made the threat ...Rxb2 real.} 18. Rab1 {
Black has to once again refrain from concrete action with} Bxc3 $6 19. Qxc3
Qxa2 20. b3 $5 $14 {The stronger 18...Nc5 reinforces all the threats, ...Rxb2
followed by ...Bxc3 and ...Ba4, or simply ...Bxc3 with queenside material
gainings.}) 18. Qxb2 Bxc3 19. Nb3 $1 {The clue to White's defence.} Bxb2 ({
Or if} 19... Qb4 20. a3 Bxb2 21. axb4 Bxa1 22. b5 Bb7 23. Rxa1 Ra8 24. Bg4 c4
25. Na5 {with excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 20. Nxa5 Ba4 21. Rab1 Bxd1
22. Bxd1 Bc3 23. Nc6 d4 24. Rb7 Nf6 25. h3 {[#]White has achieved such an
active position that he can afford a neutral move being a pawn down!} a6 26.
Be2 $44 dxe3 27. fxe3 a5 28. Bc4 Ne4 29. Bd5 Ng5 30. Kf2 {White's domination
with opposite-coloured bishops is even clearer now and Portisch went on to win
convincingly.} Re8 31. Ke2 a4 32. Kd3 Be1 33. e4 a3 34. Ra7 Bf2 35. Kc4 h5 36.
e5 h4 37. Rxa3 Bg3 38. Rb3 Ne6 39. a4 Nd4 40. Rb8 $1 Rxb8 41. Nxb8 Bxe5 42. Nd7
Bc7 43. Kxc5 Ne6+ 44. Bxe6 fxe6 45. Kc6 Bd8 46. Ne5 g6 47. Kd7 Bb6 48. Kxe6 Kg7
49. Nc6 1-0

