{White is obviously struggling to deal with Black's central pressure and
kingside space advantage. Is there a concrete way to take advantage of White's
piece congestion?} 25... Ra8 $3 {This "counter-developing" move threatens ...
Ba6, endangering the queen.} 26. a4 $2 {This simply loses material.} (26. Bxe4
{was relatively best, even though after} dxe4 $17 {[%cal Gb7a6] followed by ...
Ba6 Black's advantage would be crushing.}) (26. Rcc1 Ba6 {offers Black a
decisive attack:} 27. Qc2 (27. Qb3 a4 $19 {does not change anything.}) 27...
Nxf2 $1 28. Kxf2 Qxe3+ 29. Kf1 Bxd4 30. Rxd4 Qxd4 $19) (26. Nc3 {is best met
with} h3 $1 $17 27. g3 $6 Ba6 28. Ncb5 Bxd4 29. exd4 Qf5 {Suddenly, White has
serious kingside problems.} 30. a4 Rac8 31. Re2 Rc4 {with crushing pressure.}
32. Bxe4 $2 dxe4 33. Qxc4 $2 Qf3 $19) 26... Ba6 27. Qb3 (27. Nb5 Nxf2 28. Kxf2
Bxe3+ 29. Ke1 Qxh2 $19) 27... Bc4 28. Rxc4 dxc4 29. Qxc4 Nxf2 $1 ({Even more
convincing than} 29... Rad8 {played in Beliavsky,A (2595)-Geller,E (2550)
Minsk 1979 (0-1, 38)}) 30. Kxf2 Qxe3+ 31. Kf1 Rad8 $19 {White cannot prevent
the black queen's intrusion to h2, for instance:} 32. Rd3 Qe5 33. Kg1 Rxd4 34.
Rxd4 Rd8 *

