{How would you use White's unnatural development?} 18... Bxc3 $1 {This
paradoxical exchange of the active bishop eliminates an important queenside
defender and wins a pawn more or less by force.} (18... Bb7 {This is only
second best, offering Black only a minimal advantage.} 19. Qd1 Bxc3 $1 {
Due to the hanging d5-pawn, Black did not have a choice already. This exchange
does not win a pawn anymore but still offers him very pleasant play.} 20. bxc3
Qf6 21. Nd4 Ba6 $15 {Ubilava,E (2465)-Pigusov,E (2455) Kharkov 1985 (½-½, 26)
}) 19. Qxc3 (19. bxc3 Ne4 20. Rd4 Bb5 $17 {[%csl Gc3] wins the c3-pawn.}) 19...
Bb5 20. Rc1 ({Forced as} 20. Rfd1 Ne4 $17 {wins the exchange.}) 20... Na4 (
20... Nd3 21. Rxd3 $5 $44 {offers White good compensation for the queen.}) 21.
Qxc8 Qxc8 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 $17 {The back rank weakness and bishop's vulnerability
will cost White the b2-pawn.} *

