1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. cxd5 {
This used to be the main line a long time ago until it turned out that Black
had no special problems with handling the hanging pawns with the bishop on e6.}
Nxd5 {The safest answer.} (8... exd5 {is supposed to define the structure too
soon. I have played this structure in a series of games and I believe that
Black has an adequate play, but the main move is just simpler.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 Bb7
10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 c5) 9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 ({A more precise move order than
} 10... c5 11. Ne5 Nbd7 {as played by Beliavsky several times during his
Candidates' Match with Kasparov. The most critical game went} 12. Bf5 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Ne8 14. Bg3 $36 {Kasparov,G (2690) -Beliavsky,A (2570) Moskau 1983 (1-0,
38)}) 11. Qc2 ({This is the most aggressive regrouping. If} 11. Qe2 c5 {
play transposes to a position examined in line 8.}) 11... c5 12. Rad1 {with
certain attacking chances for White.}) 9. Bxe7 ({Avoiding all the exchanges
wastes time.} 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bg3 (10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {transposes}) 10... c5 {
With the queen on d8, Black can create the hanging pawns at once as d5 is not
hanging.} 11. Be2 (11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Be2 Be6 13. O-O {Now 13...Nc6 transposes
below but after the early exchange on c5 Black can also play the flexible.} Nd7
14. Bb5 {Kovac,L (2238)-Koval,M (2068) Slovakia 2010 (1-0, 43)} Qc8 15. Rc1 a6
16. Bd3 Qb7 17. b3 a5 18. Bb1 Nf6 19. Be5 Rfc8 20. Qd3 g6 {with excellent
counterplay for Black based on ...a5-a4. Now the main threat is ...Bf5, though,
neutralizing any attacking attempts.}) 11... Nc6 12. dxc5 (12. O-O c4 $1 13. b3
b5 14. a4 {Otherwise Black connects the rooks and, being prepared to meet
a2-a4 with ...a7-a6 maintains his space advantage.} Na5 15. axb5 $1 Nxb3 16.
Rb1 {Otherwise ...Bd7 wins the pawn on b5. But now ...Bd7xb5 would not be a
threat due to Rxb3.} a6 17. b6 Qxb6 18. Nd2 a5 19. Nxb3 cxb3 20. Rxb3 Bb4 $15)
12... bxc5 13. O-O Be6 $11 {and Black has little to fear.}) (9. Bg3 c5 {
transposes above after} 10. Nxd5 exd5 {or to other lines below.}) 9... Qxe7 10.
Nxd5 {The most principled move.} (10. Bd3 {offers Black easy play in the
spirit of the Semi-Tarrasch system with the difference that Black is more
advanced with his development.} Nxc3 (10... Bb7 $5 $11) 11. bxc3 Bb7 12. O-O c5
13. Qe2 Nc6 14. Be4 Rac8 15. Rfc1 Na5 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Nd2 Qd5 (17... cxd4 18.
cxd4 Rc7) 18. c4 Qd7 19. Nb3 cxd4 20. exd4 Qa4 $15 {Georgiev,V (2513)-Azarov,S
(2584) Dayton 2017 (0-1, 36)}) (10. Rc1 Bb7 {transposes to line 3.}) 10... exd5
11. Rc1 {White starts putting pressure on c5 already in anticipation of the ...
c7-c5 break.} ({Neutral play offers Black excellent chances:} 11. Be2 Be6 12.
O-O (12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. O-O Qf8 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rfc1 Nd7 17. b3 a5 {
Marovic, D-Ciric, D Zenica 1963 (½-½, 31)}) 12... c5 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Rfc1 c4 {
With his development almost complete, Black is ready to gain queenside space
without offering White too much in the centre and on the kingside.} 15. b3 b5
16. Qa5 Rfb8 17. bxc4 bxc4 18. Rab1 Qd8 19. Qxd8+ Rxd8 20. Nd2 Nf6 $1 (20...
Rab8 {allowed White to carry out an optimal regrouping.} 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 22. Nb1
Rb2 23. Nc3 $11 {Larsen,B-Portisch,L Porec (m) 1968 (1-0, 41)}) 21. f3 Bf5 22.
Rb5 Rab8 $15 23. Bxc4 Rbc8 24. e4 Bd7 25. Ra5 dxc4 $17) (11. Bd3 {looks more
active but it allows} c5 {at once as d5 is not hanging.} 12. dxc5 (12. O-O c4
$1 13. Bb1 Nc6 14. Qc2 {Guliev,S (2470)-Pushkov,N (2430) Orel 1992 (0-1, 47)}
g6 15. Qc3 (15. b3 b5 16. a4 Na5 $1 $15) 15... Re8 {Preventing Ne5 and
preparing ...b5-b4.} 16. e4 {What else?} Bg4 $5 17. exd5 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Qg5+ 19.
Kh1 Ne7 20. Qxc4 Nxd5 21. Be4 Rad8 {With at least enough compensation for the
pawn. The knight is dangerous in view of the kingside weaknesses and, after
Bxd5, the pawns on f3 and d4 would become even weaker.}) (12. b3 Bg4 $5 13.
dxc5 bxc5 14. h3 Be6 15. O-O Nd7 16. Rc1 Nf6 17. Nd2 Rfd8 18. Qe2 a5 19. e4 a4
20. e5 Nd7 21. f4 f5 22. exf6 Qxf6 $11 {Velikov,P (2475)-Van der Sterren,P 
(2460) Albena 1983 (½-½, 38)}) 12... bxc5 13. O-O Be6 14. Rc1 Nd7 15. Bb1 (
15. e4 {is premature as Black's pieces are optimally placed for the fight for
the c4-square.} d4 16. Nd2 (16. h3 Rfb8 17. b3 a5 18. Nd2 a4 19. bxa4 Rb4 20.
Bb5 {Jakubowski,K (2517)-Cyborowski,L (2517) Czech Republic 2017 (½-½, 34)}
Nb6 21. a3 Rb2 22. f4 Bd7 $15) 16... Ne5 17. Bb1 c4 18. h3 g5 $17 {Sasikiran,K
(2573)-Bruzon Batista,L (2534) Yerevan 2000 (0-1, 51)}) 15... Rfc8 16. Qd3 (16.
Qd2 {Boruchovsky,A (2542)-Tang,A (2513) chess.com INT 2018 (½-½, 39)} a5)
16... Nf6 17. Qa3 Qf8 18. h3 a5 19. b3 {Trichkov,V (2415)-Kotan,L (2370)
Slovakia 1996 (1-0, 66)} a4 20. bxa4 c4 21. Qxf8+ Kxf8 22. Bc2 Bd7 $15 {
The weakness of a2 is more important than that on d5.}) ({The only idea behind
} 11. Qb3 {is to play Qa3 quickly with a possible transposition to the main
line.} Be6 12. Be2 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. O-O (14. Rc1 Nd7 {transposes below})
14... Qf8 {with similar play as in the main line.}) (11. Qa4 c5 12. Qa3 {
is the same.}) 11... Be6 $1 {The bishop stands better here than on b7. It is
well defended and does not spoil the other pieces' development. The last move
is the best way to prove that the exchange in the centre was a bit premature.}
12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 (13. dxc5 {usually leads to a transposition.} bxc5 14. Qa3
Rc8 15. Nd4 $5 {The only way to give the game an independent character.} Nd7 (
15... a5 $5 {prevents Ba6.} 16. Be2 Nd7 17. O-O Nf6 $11) 16. Ba6 Re8 (16...
Rcb8 $5 $11 {is an interesting exchange sacrifice which White better avoids.}
17. Nc6 $6 Qg5 $1 18. Nxb8 Rxb8 {Attacking g2 and threatening to cage the
bishop with ...c5-c4.} 19. Bf1 d4 $17) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 (17... Qxe6 18. Bb5 d4 $11
) 18. Be2 c4 19. Qc3 Rab8 20. O-O Qb4 21. b3 cxb3 22. axb3 Qxb3 23. Qc7 Rb7 24.
Qd6 Nf6 25. Bd1 (25. Rc8 {is relatively better but Black does not have
problems after} Qb6 26. Rc6 Qb4) 25... Qb4 $15 {1/2-1/2 (53) Van der Werf,M 
(2422)-Dambacher,M (2297) Amsterdam 2002}) 13... Rc8 {Black defends his
central pawns well. After developing the knight he needs to defend the queen
in order to threaten ...c5-c4, thus more or less forcing dxc5.} 14. Bb5 {
The main theoretical discussion concluded a long time ago, shortly after it
began, actually. But I have examined it in some detail as it continues to pop
up even in games between strong players. The main idea is to dominate the
knight and to force Black to spoil his coordination on his way to completing
his development.} Qb7 $1 {This move was found by Geller after the game quoted
below. He had mentioned it to Spassky, but for some reasons the then World
Champion did not play it against Fischer when given the occasion. White is
forced to accept the pawn sacrifice as otherwise, the bishop would simply stand
badly on b5. The immediate threat is ...c5-c4.} (14... a6 $6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16.
O-O Ra7 17. Be2 Nd7 (17... a5 18. Rc3 Nd7 19. Rfc1 $14 {was the first game
where White played 14.Bb5, Furman,S-Geller,E Moscow 1970 (1-0, 32)}) 18. Nd4
Qf8 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. e4 $14 d4 $2 21. f4 Qe7 22. e5 Rb8 23. Bc4 $18 {Fischer,
R-Spassky,B Reykjavik 1972 (1-0, 41)}) (14... Nd7 {is actually entirely
playable, as after} 15. Bxd7 (15. O-O Rc7 $5 $146 16. Rfd1 Nf6 $11) 15... Qxd7
16. dxc5 bxc5 $11 {the pawn is taboo:} 17. Rxc5 $2 Rxc5 18. Qxc5 Rc8 $19 {
followed by ...Rc1+ wins a rook.}) 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rxc5 Rxc5 17. Qxc5 Na6 $1
{Geller's point. More about it in the strategic article accompanying the
database.} 18. Bxa6 (18. Qc6 Qxc6 19. Bxc6 Rb8 20. O-O (20. b3 $2 {cuts the
bishop's retreat to d1 and loses material to} Rc8 21. Nd4 Nb4 $19) 20... Rxb2
21. a4 Nb4 22. Nd4 Ra2 $15 {Zhidkov,V (2420)-Zarubin,P (2415) Podolsk 1993 
(0-1, 48)}) 18... Qxa6 19. Qa3 Qc4 $1 ({All of this has been well known for a
long time so it is curious that a modern game went} 19... Qxa3 20. bxa3 Rb8 21.
O-O Rb2 22. Ra1 $11 {Ni,H (2674)-Ma,Q (2637) China 2017 (½-½, 31)}) 20. Kd2 (
20. Qc3 Rb8 21. Nd2 ({Relatively better is} 21. Qxc4 dxc4 22. b3 cxb3 23. axb3
Rxb3 24. O-O Rb2 25. Nd4 Bd7 26. f3 a5 $15 {following Geller's analysis.})
21... Qxa2 22. O-O Qxb2 $17 {L'Ami,A (2289)-Sharevich,A (2305) Panevezys 2007 
(½-½, 53)}) 20... Qg4 21. Rg1 d4 $1 22. exd4 {Not really an improvement over
the old game as the king will be very exposed anyway, while the bishop will be
very strong after getting the blockading square on d5..} (22. Nxd4 Qh4 23. Re1
Qxf2+ (23... Bc4 24. f3 Qxh2 $17) 24. Re2 Qf1 25. Nxe6 fxe6 26. Qd6 Kh8 $17 {
Timman, J-Geller,E Hilversum 1973 (0-1, 36)}) 22... Bd5 (22... Rb8 $5 23. b4 a5
$17 {leaves the king exposed from all sides.}) 23. h3 Qf5 24. Re1 Rb8 25. Qc3
Bxa2 26. Re5 Qb1 27. Qc2 Qf1 $17 {Kuzubov,Y (2603)-Schroll,G (2410) Plovdiv
2008 (0-1, 37)} *

