1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. cxd5
Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. Be2 {
This is the soundest move. White continues his development without trying to
refute Black's plan. The position remains interesting but White has no chances
for an advantage.} Nd7 15. O-O Qf8 {I prefer this over the other way of
defending the queen.} (15... Kf8 {brings the king close to the centre which
can be useful only in the endgame. With many pieces on board, certain accuracy
is needed.} 16. Ba6 (16. dxc5 bxc5 17. b3 a5 18. Bb5 Nb6 19. Qb2 Kg8 20. a4 Nd7
21. Rfd1 Nf6 22. Ne5 Rc7 23. Nd3 Bg4 24. Rd2 {(½-½, 71) Hertneck,G (2496)
-Bacrot,E (2723) Germany 2017} Rac8 $11) 16... Rc7 17. dxc5 bxc5 (17... Nxc5 {
½-½ Averbakh,Y (2490)-Vasiukov,E (2495) Moscow 1982} 18. Be2 Rac8 19. Nd4 Bd7
) 18. Nd4 Nb6 19. Nxe6+ fxe6 20. e4 Kg8 $11) 16. dxc5 {White should not ignore
the threat ...c5-c4, offering Black a mobile queenside majority.} (16. Ba6 {
only temporarily spoils Black's coordination. In view of the permanent
possibility of ...c5-c4, even after dxc5, ...bxc5, the bishop could land into
some trouble.} Rc7 17. dxc5 (17. b3 {takes measures against ...c5-c4 but after
the bishop's departure from e2 Black can create some kingside counterplay.} Bg4
18. Nd2 Qe7 {[%cal Ge7g5] Planning . ..Qg5.} 19. h3 Bf5 20. Rfd1 Rd8 21. Nf3
Nf6 22. Qb2 Be4 $11) 17... bxc5 18. Nd4 c4 19. Qxf8+ Rxf8 20. e4 {Boruchovsky,
A (2536)-Nakar,E (2463) Douglas 2015 (½-½, 24)} Ne5 $11) (16. Rfd1 c4 17.
Qxf8+ Kxf8 {is very pleasant for Black.}) (16. b3 c4 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 18. bxc4
dxc4 19. e4 b5 {and Black's pawns are at least as dangerous as White's.}) 16...
bxc5 17. Rfd1 (17. Nd2 {Preparing e3-e4, but as in so many other cases the
overall activity and the later control on d3 compensates for Black's minimal
structural deffects.} Rab8 ({The simplest is} 17... c4 $11 {by similarity with
the main line.}) 18. e4 d4 (18... dxe4 19. Nxe4 c4 20. Nd6 Rc6 21. Rfd1 Nb6 $11
) 19. f4 f5 (19... f6 $11) 20. e5 Nb6 21. Nc4 Nxc4 22. Bxc4 Qf7 23. b3 $14 {
Flohr,S-Kasparian,G Leningrad 1947 (½-½, 55)}) (17. Qa5 Qd6 18. b3 Qb6 19.
Qa4 {Vlasenko,M (2351)-Vasilevich,I (2277) St Petersburg 2004 (0-1, 43)} a5
$132) 17... a5 $1 {A typical way of gaining space and putting the enemy queen
in a slightly incomfiortable position.} 18. Rd2 (18. Nd2 c4 $1 {The usual
reaction when the knight releases the control over d4.} 19. Qxf8+ Kxf8 20. e4
Ne5 {½-½ Szabo,L-Filip,M Beverwijk 1966}) 18... a4 19. Rdc2 Rcb8 20. Nd2 c4
$1 {With the white knight far from d4, this is entirely well-timed. Black
suddenply puts all his pieces to work.} ({Black could also play a neutral move
such as} 20... Rb6 $5) 21. Qxf8+ {This prematurely weakens the defence on b2.}
(21. e4 {is safer.} Qxa3 (21... Ne5 $5) 22. bxa3 dxe4 23. Nxe4 Ne5 24. Nd6 Nd3
$11) 21... Kxf8 22. e4 (22. Nf3 a3 23. bxa3 Nc5 24. Nd4 Rxa3 $17) (22. a3 Ne5
23. Nb1 Rb3 24. Nc3 Rab8 25. Nxa4 Bd7 26. Nc5 Rxb2 27. Nxd7+ Nxd7 $15) (22. Nb1
Bf5 23. Rd2 Bxb1 24. Rxb1 a3 $17 25. b4 cxb3 26. axb3 Nc5 27. Bd1 a2 28. Ra1
Nxb3) 22... Ne5 23. exd5 Bxd5 (23... Bf5 24. Nxc4 Bxc2 25. Rxc2 Nxc4 26. Bxc4
Ra5 $15) 24. Nxc4 Nxc4 25. Bxc4 Bxc4 26. Rxc4 Rxb2 27. Ra1 a3 $15 {Lou,Y (2412)
-Zhou,J (2590) Beijing 2012 (½-½, 53)} *

