1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Rc1 {
This natural move has independent value only from the point of view of the
main line below. Otherwise, it would transpose to other lines, in which the
rook is not always optimally placed on c1.} Bb7 9. cxd5 ({The lines I was
referring to as having little independent value start with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10.
cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 (11. b4 c6 12. Qb3 a5 13. bxa5 Rxa5 14. Be2 Nd7 15. O-O Qa8
16. a4 c5 $11 {Savchenko,B (2602)-Galkin,A (2615) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 (0-1,
74) The rook usually stands on a1 or goes to b1 in this structure.}) ({As we
will see, in the setups with} 11. Be2 {the rooks many times go to e1 and d1.})
11... c5 {and play at best transposes to Line 7.}) 9... Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11.
Nxd5 {Delaying this exchange does not change much:} (11. Be2 c5 12. dxc5 Rd8
13. Qb3 Nd7 {With the usual counterplay based on the white queen's
vulnerability.}) (11. Bd3 {does not avoid this problem:} c5 12. dxc5 Rd8 13.
Qe2 Nd7 14. cxb6 Nc5) (11. Bc4 {only looks more active than those moves above
as the bishop will soon be exposed along the c-file.} Nxc3 {For once, Black
has to exchange knights before breaking in the centre.} 12. bxc3 (12. Rxc3 Nd7
13. O-O {½-½ Kortschnoj, V (2635)-Beliavsky, A (2625) Vienna 1986} c5 {is
obviously not worse for Black.}) 12... c5 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qe2 Rc7 $5 {Delaying
White's planned Ba6 for one more move. Black will next play ...Nd7 followed by
...Rac8 with some problems for White along the c-file.}) 11... Bxd5 {In order
to achieve equal (and sometimes even more pleasant) play, Black needs to carry
out ...c7-c5, preferably without getting a weak pawn on c5.} ({With the bishop
on b7 and after the recent exchanges,} 11... exd5 {looks less appealing but is
entirely playable.}) 12. Bd3 (12. Be2 c5 13. dxc5 Rd8 $1 14. Qa4 (14. Qc2 Rc8
15. O-O Rxc5 16. Qd2 Nd7 17. b4 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Nf6 19. a3 a5 $11 {Ribli,Z (2605)
-Beliavsky,A (2640) Montpellier 1985 (½-½, 74)}) 14... Nd7 $1 {Being better
developed, Black, can resort to this pseudo-sacrifice. This will be a
permanent issue in the lines below.} 15. e4 (15. cxb6 axb6 16. Qd4 Nc5 $17) (
15. b4 a5 $15) (15. c6 Nc5 16. Qa3 a5 {½-½ Aseev,K (2575)-Khalifman,A (2615)
Leningrad 1990} 17. O-O Bxc6 $15) 15... Nxc5 16. Rxc5 Qxc5 17. exd5 Qc1+ 18.
Bd1 (18. Qd1 Qxb2 $17 {is a much worse form for White of the game position.})
18... Rxd5 19. O-O Qxb2 20. Bb3 Rc5 21. Qa6 Rc7 22. g3 Rd8 {Black is not worse
from a0 material point of view and the endgame could be even better for him.}
23. Re1 Rc1 $11 24. Qxa7 $2 Rxe1+ 25. Nxe1 Qe2 26. Nc2 Rd1+ {½-½ Kortschnoj,
V (2625)-Short,N (2635) Wijk aan Zee 1990} 27. Kg2 Qe4+ 28. Kh3 Rd2 $17 29.
Qb8+ (29. Qxb6 $2 Qh1 30. Bc4 g5 $19) 29... Kh7 30. Qf4 Qxf4 31. gxf4 Rxf2 32.
Kg3 Rd2 $17) 12... c5 13. dxc5 {The critical line, but also quite risky.} (13.
O-O {may be safer.} Nd7 14. e4 (14. Bb1 Rac8 15. Qd3 Nf6 {stops White's attack.
}) 14... Bb7 15. b4 $5 {The only try to make the game more interesting.} Rfc8 (
{Actually} 15... cxb4 {is playable} 16. Rc7 Bc8 $13 17. Qa4 Nc5 18. Qc6 Qd8 19.
dxc5 Qxd3 $17) 16. bxc5 (16. dxc5 bxc5 17. b5 a6 18. a4 axb5 19. axb5 c4 20.
Bxc4 Bxe4 21. Re1 Bb7 22. Nd4 {Gislason,G (2305) -Sigurjonsson,G (2465)
Iceland 1995 (1-0, 37)} Nb6 23. Bb3 Rxc1 24. Qxc1 Qb4 25. Rd1 Rd8 $15) 16...
bxc5 17. Qb3 Nf6 $5 {Black could defend his bishop with one of the rooks, but
this leads to more interesting play.} 18. dxc5 Nxe4 19. c6 Rxc6 20. Bxe4 Rxc1
21. Qxb7 Rxf1+ 22. Kxf1 Qxb7 23. Bxb7 Rb8 24. Ba6 Rb4 25. Bd3 Ra4 26. Bb1 g5
27. Ke2 Kg7 28. Nd2 f5 29. Kd3 Rf4 30. Ke2 Rh4 31. h3 Ra4 {½-½ Beliavsky,
A-Geller,E Yerevan 1975}) 13... Rd8 14. Qe2 (14. cxb6 axb6 15. a3 {offers
Black strong initiative.} Nd7 16. Qe2 (16. e4 Bb7 17. Qe2 Nc5) (16. Bb1 Nc5 17.
Qe2 Bb7 {Preventing the castle in view of ...Ba6.} 18. b4 Nd3+ $1 {A
pseudo-sacrifice maintaining Black's initiative.} 19. Bxd3 Rxa3 {The bishop is
terribly misplaced on d3.} 20. Ne5 (20. Rd1 Qxb4+ 21. Kf1 Rdxd3 22. Rxd3 Ba6
$19) (20. Bb1 Qxb4+ 21. Nd2 Bxg2 22. Rg1 Bf3 $1) 20... Qxb4+ 21. Qd2 Qxd2+ 22.
Kxd2 f6) 16... Bxf3 17. gxf3 Ne5 18. Be4 (18. Bb1 Qg5 19. Kf1 Qh5 20. Kg2 Rd2
21. Qxd2 Qxf3+ 22. Kg1 Qg4+ 23. Kf1 Qh3+ 24. Ke2 Qf3+ $19) (18. Rc3 Qg5 19. Kf1
Qh5 20. f4 Qh3+ 21. Ke1 Qg2 $17) 18... f5 19. Bxa8 Nd3+ 20. Kf1 Nxc1 21. Qc2
Nd3 $15) (14. O-O Nd7 $5 $146 15. e4 Bxa2 16. b4 bxc5 17. Qc2 c4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4
19. Qxc4 Nb6 $11) 14... Nc6 (14... Nd7 15. e4 Bb7 16. c6 Rac8 17. Bb5 (17. c7
Rf8 $11) 17... Nb8 $11) 15. b3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ne5 17. Be4 Rac8 18. f4 Rxc5 19.
O-O f5 20. Rxc5 Qxc5 21. Bxf5 {½-½ Kopta,P (2324)-Benco,P (2158) Stare Mesto
2005} exf5 22. fxe5 Qxe5 $11 *

