1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Be2 {
This apparently modest developing move leaves the d-file open and is thus
aimed to inhibit ...c7-c5.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is a typical exchange in many
lines below. White gives up the bishop pair in the hope of proving that the
d5-square and other light squares are weak after ...c7-c5.} (9. O-O {[%emt 0:
00:04] is examined in Line}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 {This is one of
White's main ideas. He takes measures against ...c7-c5, which is best done
with the bishop on e2. Against other moves, Black is best adviced to react in
the same way as in the main line starting with 11...c6. Even though the
position looks simple, we will soon see that Black has to display certain
accuracy when choosing his move order.} (11. O-O c5 (11... c6 $1) 12. dxc5 Bxc3
(12... bxc5 13. Qb3 Bc6 14. Rad1) 13. bxc3 bxc5 14. Rb1 Qc7 15. Ne5 Nd7 16.
Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Qb3 Bc6 18. Qa3 Qe7 19. Bf3 $14 {Kramnik,V (2758)-Khalifman,A 
(2656) Linares 2000 (½-½, 49)}) (11. Rc1 c6 {leads to a position where the
rook is not optimally placed on c1.}) (11. Qb3 c6 {is a comfortable version of
line 6.}) 11... c6 ({There have been intense disputes after} 11... c5 12. bxc5
bxc5 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Bb5 {Black seems to be able to hold on to a
draw, but he is mainly struggling. The recommended move leads to more complex
play and offers both sides chances.}) 12. O-O Re8 $1 {Preventing an early Ne5
is the most accurate move order.} (12... a5 13. b5 c5 14. Ne5 $14) (12... Nd7
13. Qb3 Re8 (13... a5 14. b5 {leaves Black hanging. I was amused to find many
correspondence games continuing with} a4 15. Nxa4 c5 {It is really hard to 100%
justify the pawn sacrifice, but computers think differently. True, their
enthusiasm slows down a bit as the games advance. I have inserted the only
over the board game with this line which is the only one making sense from a
human point of view.} 16. Nc3 c4 17. Qb2 Qe7 18. a4 Rfe8 19. Nd2 Nf8 20. Bf3
Qd7 21. g3 g6 22. Bg2 h5 23. Rae1 Ne6 24. Qc2 h4 25. Qd1 Kg7 26. Qg4 Rad8 27.
Rc1 hxg3 28. hxg3 Rh8 29. Bh3 Bg5 30. Bg2 f5 31. Qe2 {In Porat,M (2295)
-Muminova, N (2329) Istanbul 2012 (0-1, 65) Black carelessly allowed f2-f4 with
a gain of time followed by Nf3 with a clear advantage. Better was} Bf6 $5 $44 {
maintaining the kingside counterplay as} 32. f4 $2 Nxd4 33. exd4 Bxd4+ 34. Rf2
Rhe8 $17 {and we can see that White's task of converting his extra pawn is
anything but simple, but I still prefer avoiding the pawn sacrifice.}) 14. Rad1
(14. b5 c5 15. Nxd5 Bxd4 $1 16. Rad1 Ne5 17. exd4 c4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Nb4 Na5
20. Qd3 Qd6 21. Nc2 Be4 22. Qe2 {Onischuk,A (2655)-Kosyrev,V (2565) Moscow
2002 (1-0, 41)} Nc4 $1 23. Qxc4 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Qg6+ 25. Kh1 Rac8 26. Qd3 Qxd3
27. Rxd3 Rxc2 $11) (14. Rfd1 Nf8 15. a4 a5 16. b5 c5 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Rac1 c4
19. Qc2 Rc8 20. Qd2 Rc5 $11) 14... a5 {What else?!} 15. b5 a4 $5 $146 {This
has never been played but it looks like Black's best chance to keep an optimal
central configuration.} 16. Nxa4 c5 17. Nc3 c4 18. Qc2 {The same evaluation as
above applies. The line may be good as a "one day experiment", but I would
not build up a repertoire around it.}) 13. Qb3 (13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Qb3 Nd7 15.
Rfd1 a5 16. b5 c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qa3 Rac8 19. Nd4 Be5 20. g3 $11 {illisible,
Vovk,Y (2592)-Fedorchuk,S (2669) Vandoeuvre 2014 (0-1)}) 13... a5 $1 {Right in
time before White increases his pressure on d5.} ({If} 13... b5 14. a4 a6 15.
a5 $1 $14 {Black does not have the manoeuvre ...Nd7-b6-c4 while after Nc5 the
pawn on a6 would be a permanent weakness.}) 14. b5 (14. a3 {leads to exactly
the opposite with respect to the line above:} Nd7 15. Rfd1 b5 16. Ne1 {
Wisskirchen,A-Barsov,A (2425) Germany 1994 (½-½, 34)} Nb6 17. Nd3 a4 18. Qc2
g6 19. Nc5 Bc8 $15 {It is now the pawn on a3 which is a permanent weakness.
With the queenside stable Black can start his kingside play, possibly with ...
Ra7-e7.}) (14. bxa5 Rxa5 15. a4 {leads to a structure where Black has little
trouble defending b6 and carrying out ...c6-c5-c4.} Nd7 16. Rfd1 (16. Rfe1 c5
$5 $146 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 cxd4 19. Bb5 Ne5 $11) (16. Rad1 g6 17. Rfe1 Bg7
18. e4 Nf8 19. exd5 cxd5 20. Rb1 Ne6 $11 {Hawkins,J (2533)-Adams,M (2758)
Douglas 2014 (½-½, 35)}) 16... Be7 (16... g6 17. Rab1 Bg7 18. Ne1 {Lukacs,
P-Zinn,L Decin 1973 (1-0, 28)} h5 19. Nd3 Bf8 {[%cal Gf8d6]} 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21.
dxe5 Rxe5 22. Qxb6 Qxb6 23. Rxb6 Ba8 24. Rb8 Kg7 $15) 17. Rab1 (17. e4 dxe4 18.
Nxe4 Bf8 19. Nfd2 b5 $5 $132) 17... Bd6 {The start of an interesting
regrouping aimed at over defending b6.} 18. g3 Bc7 19. Bf1 {Carlsen,M (2714)
-Kramnik,V (2785) Moscow (blitz) 2007 (½-½, 42)} Bc8 20. Bg2 Nf6 21. Ne5 Bxe5
22. dxe5 Ng4 23. Qxb6 Nxe5 $11) 14... c5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rad1 (16. Rac1 {
was played twice in the match Timman,J (2635)-Short,N (2655) El Escorial 1993}
a4 $5 {For once this is very strong.} 17. Nxa4 c4 18. Qc2 Qa5 19. Bd1 Nd7 $15)
16... Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Nd7 18. Rd2 Rc8 19. Rfd1 Nf6 20. Qb2 Qb6 (20... Ne4 21. Rc2
a4 $132) 21. Rc2 Ne4 $11 22. Ne5 Qf6 23. f4 d4 24. Bc4 Nd6 $15 {Van Wely,L 
(2655)-Asrian,K (2646) Turin 2006 (½-½, 42)} *

