1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Be2
Bb7 9. O-O {This allows Black to complete his development unhindered. And yet,
the resulting position with hanging pawns remains interesting.} Nbd7 10. Rc1 c5
{Now and on the next move Black could open the centre with 10...dxc4 and 11...
Nxd5, respectively. But I prefer the complex positions with hanging pawns.} 11.
cxd5 (11. Bg3 Ne4 12. Nxe4 (12. cxd5 Nxg3 13. hxg3 exd5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nd4 {
Schirowski,C-Frietsch,D Germany 2001 (0-1, 36)} Bf6 $11) 12... dxe4 13. Ne5
Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 {½-½ Savon, V-Ivkov,B Petropolis 1973} 16.
dxc5 bxc5 17. Qc2 Bc6 18. Rfd1 Rfb8 19. Rd2 a5 20. Rcd1 Qe5 $11) (11. Qa4 dxc4
{leaves the queen misplaced as after} 12. Bxc4 a6 {Black gains time for his
counterplay.}) 11... exd5 12. Qa4 $5 {The most interesting move. White
provokes ...a7-a6 hoping to make use of the relative weakness on b6.} (12. Qc2
Rc8 13. Rfd1 Ne4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. dxc5 Rxc5 (15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 bxc5 17. Qa3
Nf6 18. Qxa7 Rc7 19. Qb6 d4) 16. Qb3 Ndf6 17. Nxe4 (17. Nd4 Rfc8 18. Qa3 Nxc3
19. Rxc3 Ne4 20. Rcd3 Qh4 21. g3 Qf6 22. f3 Ra5 23. Qb4 Nd6 $11) (17. Nb5 $2
Ng4 $17) (17. h3 Rfc8 18. Qa3 Qc7 $11) 17... dxe4 18. Nd4 Rfc8 19. Qa3 Bd5 20.
Nb5 a5 21. Rxc5 Rxc5 22. Nc3 Qe5 23. Qa4 g6 24. h3 Kg7 25. Qd4 Qxd4 26. Rxd4
Bc6 $11 {Agzamov,G-Geller,E (2575) Moscow 1983 (½-½, 71)}) (12. Ne5 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Ne4 14. Nxe4 (14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. f4 {Lang,H-Dralle,F Neumuenster 1999 
(½-½, 19)} (15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qd6 Rfe8 $15) (15. Nxd5 Qxe5 $17 {Reisel,F 
(2110)-Barczi,T (2125) Slovakia 2005 (1-0, 47)}) 15... Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Rad8 $15 {
[%cal Gf7f6,Gd5d4]}) 14... dxe4 15. Qxd8 Bxd8 16. Bg3 Be7 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. Bc4
Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ {½-½ Bromberger,S (2518) -Jussupow,A (2566) Bad
Wiessee 2009}) (12. dxc5 bxc5 {is less problematic.} 13. Rc2 (13. Qc2 Rc8 14.
Rfd1 Qb6 15. Qb1 Rfd8 16. Rc2 Qe6 17. Bg3 Nh5 18. Rcd2 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Nf6 20.
Qc2 g6 21. Qa4 a6 22. Bd3 Kg7 23. Bb1 Qb6 24. a3 d4 $1 $19 {Kortschnoj,V (2650)
-Karpov,A (2690) Merano 1981 (0-1, 43) We have examined this game in the
strategic section.}) 13... Qb6 $1 14. Rd2 Qe6 15. Qb3 Bc6 (15... Rab8 16. Bg3
Bd6 $11 {Kasparov}) 16. Rfd1 Rfb8 (16... Rfe8 17. Bg3 Nb6 18. Ne5 Bb7 19. Nb5
Bd8 $11) 17. Qc2 Bf8 18. Bg3 Rb7 19. h3 g6 (19... Re8 20. Ne1 Ne5 $11 21. Bxe5
Qxe5 22. Nd3 Qg5 23. Bf3 Rc7 $11) 20. Ne1 Re8 (20... Ne5) 21. Bf3 Nb6 {We can
see that Black mainly cares about defending his pawns. The moment for breaking
in the centre will arise at some point.} 22. b3 Rc8 23. Nd3 d4 24. Nf4 Qe8 25.
exd4 Bxf3 26. gxf3 cxd4 (26... c4 27. d5 cxb3 28. axb3 Bb4 29. Rd3 Nfxd5 30.
Nfxd5 Nxd5 31. Rxd5 Bxc3 32. Rc1 Rd7 33. Rxd7 Qxd7 $11 {[%cal Gc8c5]} 34. Be5
$2 Rc5 35. Bxc3 Qxh3 $19) 27. Rxd4 Qc6 28. Nfe2 $2 (28. R1d3 $14) 28... Nfd5
29. Rc4 (29. Rc1 Bg7 $17) 29... Nxc4 30. Nxd5 Nb6 $17 {Kwatschewsky,L (2325)
-Lobron,E (2505) Beersheba 1985 (0-1, 41)}) 12... a6 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfd1 Qb6
15. Qb3 $5 {This is the point. With the pawn on a7, Black could keep the queen
