1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Qb3 {
This is the most direct way of putting pressure on d5. On the other hand, this
also involves an early commitment.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {The only consequent follow-up.
After other continuations, the queen would soon be exposed on b3.} (9. Rd1 Nbd7
10. cxd5 (10. Be2 c5) 10... Nxd5 (10... exd5 $146 11. Be2 c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13.
Qc2 Rc8 $11) 11. Bxe7 (11. Bg3 c5 12. Bc4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nc5 14. Qc2 Nxc3 15.
Qxc3 Ne4 16. Qb3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 {Bykhovsky,A (2496)-Cheng,B (2520) chess.com
2019 (0-1, 39)} Qc7 $15) 11... Qxe7 12. Bc4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 c5 $15 {½-½ Kallio,
H (2474) -Pecorelli Garcia,H (2451) Santa Clara 2003} 14. Be2 (14. O-O Bxf3 15.
gxf3 Qh4 $36) 14... a6 15. a4 Rfb8 16. O-O b5 $15) (9. c5 Qc8 $5 $146 10. cxb6
axb6 $15) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {The continuation of the same policy.
} (11. Bd3 {allows} c5 12. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {making use of the exposed position of
the white queen.} 13. c6 {is the best, gaining a tempo over 11.0-0.} (13. O-O
Nxc5 14. Qc2 Qe7 (14... d4 $11) 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Rac1 g6 17. Nd4 Rac8 18. Qb1
Ne4 (18... Kg7 {1/2-1/2 (35) Marzolo,C (2452)-Dorfman,J (2581) Marseilles 2010}
19. Bf5 $11) 19. Nce2 Rc5 $15) (13. cxb6 $6 {is at least risky:} Nc5 14. Qc2
Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 Qxb6 16. Qd2 d4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Bb7 19. O-O-O Rfd8 {
[%cal Gb7f3]} 20. Qe2 Rac8 $40) 13... Bxc6 14. O-O Nc5 15. Qc2 d4 (15... Qe7
16. Nd4 {½-½ Jasnikowski,Z (2435)-Schandorff,L (2445) Copenhagen 1990} Bb7
$11) 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. exd4 Qxd4 18. Bf5 Rad8 19. Rad1 Qe5 20. Rfe1 Rxd1 21.
Rxd1 Re8 22. h3 g6 23. Bg4 h5 24. Be2 Ne6 $15 {/= Zaid,L-Spassky,B Moscow 1972
(½-½, 32)}) (11. Be2 {is likely to transpose if White places the rooks on
the optimal d1- and e1-squares. Deviating could leave him short of
constructive plans, as e3-e4 is not easy to carry out.} Re8 12. O-O c6 13. Rfd1
(13. Rfe1) (13. Rad1) 13... Nd7 14. Rac1 Nf8 15. Rd2 Ne6 16. Qd1 Qe7 17. a3 c5
18. dxc5 (18. Qb3 {Minzer,C (2370)-Farah,R (2260) Buenos Aires 1993 (0-1, 54)}
c4 19. Qc2 Nc7 $15 {followed by the queenside pawn attack.}) 18... Bxc3 19.
bxc3 (19. Rxc3 bxc5 $11) 19... Nxc5 $11) 11... Re8 $1 {The most precise move.
The rook stands well on e8 from the point of view of global regrouping. Short
term, it prevents White's most active way of developing.} (11... c6 12. Bd3 Nd7
