1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Bd3 {
This looks like a more active way of developing the bishop. But in the lines
examined below, Black's hanging pawns are safer due to the lack of pressure
along the d-file.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O ({With the bishop on
d3,} 11. b4 {makes less sense:} c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 cxd4 $1 {This is the
difference. White cannot keep the control on d4 with his pieces.} 14. Nxd4 Bxd4
15. exd4 Re8+ {Once again, we can notice that the bishop would have been
better placed on e2.} 16. Ne2 Ba6 $11) 11... c5 12. Rc1 (12. dxc5 bxc5 {
frees Black's play.} 13. Qb3 Bc6 14. Be2 (14. Bb5 d4 15. Bxc6 {½-½ Benjamin,
J (2530)-Seirawan,Y (2585) USA 1989}) 14... Nd7 15. Rfd1 $6 (15. Nxd5 Rb8 16.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qc3 Rxb2 18. Qxf6 Nxf6 $11) 15... Rb8 16. Qc2 Qa5 17. Nd2 {
Portisch,L (2610)-Vaganian,R (2625) Saint John 1988 (1-0, 49)} c4 $17 {We have
examined this game in the strategic article.}) 12... Nd7 13. Bf5 {Trying to
submit the hanging pawns to strong pressure.} ({The attacking} 13. Bb1 {
is easily parried, as Black holds the centre firm in his hand.} Re8 14. Qc2 g6
15. Rfd1 Rc8 {The bishop is passive now on b1.} 16. Qd2 Nf8 (16... Qe7 $5 17.
dxc5 $6 bxc5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Bxb2 20. Rc2 Nb6 21. Qb3 Bf6 $17) 17. dxc5
(17. Bd3 Ne6 18. Ne2 Re7 $15 {(½-½, 49) Lukacs,P (2455)-Kiss,L (2290)
Hungary 1993}) 17... Rxc5 18. b4 Rc8 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gf8e6]} 19. Rc2 Qe7 20.
a3 Rcd8 $11) (13. Re1 {is sound but too soft.} Re8 14. Bb5 Re7 15. dxc5 Nxc5
16. Nd4 Rc8 17. Be2 {Jussupow,A (2610)-Short,N (2650) Rotterdam 1989 (0-1, 61)}
a6 $5 {This move ensures the c7-square for the rooks, preparing a later ...
b5-b4 at the same time.}) (13. Ne2 c4 14. Bb1 Re8 15. Ng3 g6 16. Qd2 h5 $15)
13... g6 $5 {The simplest.} 14. Bxd7 (14. Bh3 Bg7 $5 $146 15. Qb3 Re8 $11 16.
Nxd5 Nf8 17. Nf4 Bxf3 18. gxf3 cxd4 $15) 14... cxd4 $1 {An important
intermediate move.} (14... Qxd7 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Ne4 Bxb2 17. Nxc5 $14) 15.
Bc6 $1 {Gaining a tempo is the best chance.} (15. exd4 Qxd7 16. Qd2 Kg7 $11 17.
Ne5 $6 Bxe5 18. dxe5 d4 19. Ne2 Qd5 20. f3 Rfd8 $15 {Mamedyarov,S (2479)
-Sargissian,G (2520) Tbilisi 2001 (½-½, 35)}) (15. Nxd4 Qxd7 {basically
offers Black a free tempo with respect to the main line.} 16. Qd3 Rac8 17. Rfd1
Rfd8 18. Rc2 Kg7 19. Rdc1 Rc5 20. h3 h5 21. Ncb5 a6 22. Nc3 Rdc8 23. b3 b5 $11
{Komarov,D (2580)-Dorfman,J (2600) St Raphael 1998 (½-½, 29)}) 15... Bxc6 16.
Nxd4 Bb7 {With two bishops versus two knights Black has not much to fear. The
point is that White needs to keep the Isolani permanently blocked so as to
avoid ...d5-d4 at the right moment.} 17. Qa4 (17. Qf3 Be5 18. Rfd1 Rc8 19. Rd2
Qe7 20. Rcd1 Rfd8 21. Nce2 Rc5 22. Nf4 Qf6 23. Nfe2 Rdc8 24. Qxf6 Bxf6 25. f3
a5 26. Nc3 Rc4 27. Ndb5 Rd8 28. Rd3 Kg7 29. Na3 Rcc8 $11 30. Na4 $2 Ba6 31. Rb3
b5 32. Nxb5 {Langeweg,K (2415)-Dutreeuw,M (2405) Forli 1991 (1-0, 40)} Rc4 $1
33. Nbc3 (33. Nac3 a4 34. Ra3 Be7 $19) 33... d4 34. exd4 Bxd4+ 35. Kh1 Bxc3 36.
Rxd8 Bf6 37. Rd1 Rxa4 $17) 17... Qe7 {½-½ Kasimdzhanov,R (2595)-Kramnik,V 
