1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Qc2 {
White prepares to castle long and launch a massive kingside pawn attack in the
hope of using the relative weakness induced by ...h7-h6. But as we will see,
the white king will also be exposed.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {The only consequent
continuation. If allowed to play ...Nbd7 and ...c7-c5 the white queen would be
exposed on c2.} (9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. e4 (
13. Qxc7 $2 Rfc8 14. Qf4 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qb4+) 13... Bb7 14. Bd3 c5 15. O-O Rac8
16. Qe2 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 $15 {Degerman,L (2480)-Haba,P (2520) Pula 1997 (0-1,
22)}) (9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Kb1 c5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 $17) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11.
O-O-O (11. g4 c5 {more or less forces} 12. O-O-O {transposing.}) 11... c5 {
Black should not hesitate any moment to launch his queenside attack.} 12. g4 (
12. h4 Nc6 {makes no big difference as White does not have anything better
than transposing. If} 13. dxc5 {he does not get much out of the fact that he
is not hanging along the long diagonal as in the next line:} Nb4 $1 14. Qb3
bxc5 15. a3 a5 $1 {A very strong piece sacrifice, putting the white king in
big danger.} 16. axb4 axb4 17. Ne4 Be7 $17 {Black is attacking and White is
not. The extra piece is not relevant at this height.}) (12. dxc5 {is examined
in the next line.}) 12... Nc6 {The simplest way to increase the pressure in
the centre.} 13. h4 {White does not have the time for second thoughts.} (13.
dxc5 $2 bxc5 (13... Nb4 {with similar play as above is also possible, of
course.}) 14. Nxd5 Nd4 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Bc4 Rac8 $19) 13...
cxd4 14. exd4 (14. Nxd4 {loses a pawn without compensation.} Nxd4 15. exd4 Bxh4
$17 {White has no attacking chances at all.} 16. Qd2 (16. f4 Bg3 17. f5 Re8 18.
Kb1 Re3 19. Bg2 Rc8 20. Qb3 Rc4 $19 {Pedersen,D (2310) -Klovans,J (2465)
Senden 1999 (0-1, 26)}) 16... f5 17. f4 (17. gxf5 Rxf5 18. Kb1 Rxf2) 17... fxg4
18. Qh2 Be7 $19 {Banikas,H (2507)-Lutz,C (2591) Corfu 1999 (0-1, 35)}) 14... g6
{Taking measures against g4-g5 and preparing the bishop's retreat to g7.} 15.
Kb1 (15. h5 {weakens the f5-square but stabilizes Black's kingside.} g5 16. Qf5
Kg7 $5 $146 {An interesting though generally desirable regrouping, proving
that White's attacking chances are not realistic.} (16... Bg7 17. Bd3 Re8 {
is also good as in Watorek,M (2103)-Bednarczyk,D (2201) Dobczyce 2017 (1-0, 33)
}) 17. Rg1 (17. Qxd5 Qc7 $19) (17. Nxd5 Nb4 18. Nxb4 Qc8+ 19. Qxc8 Raxc8+ 20.
Kb1 Bxf3 $19) (17. Bd3 Rh8 {leaves the queen vulnerable to ...Ne7 or ...Bc8xg4.
} 18. Nxd5 Nb4 19. Ne3 Qe8 $17) 17... Qc8 18. Bd3 Qxf5 19. Bxf5 Rad8 20. Ne2
Be7 $1 {Not allowing Ng3-f5.} 21. Ng3 Bd6 {With at least equal play for Black
who can play ...Bxg3 if needed.}) (15. g5 {throws away a pawn without real
compensation.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bxg5+ 17. Kb1 Qf6 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. a3 Rad8 20.
Bb5 Kg7 21. Ne2 Qf6 22. Rhg1 Rh8 23. Bd3 Bc8 24. f4 Ne7 $17 {Bellon Lopez,J 
(2445)-Lafuente,P (2524) Barbera del Valles 2009 (½-½, 39)}) 15... Bg7 16.
Bb5 (16. g5 h5 $15) ({With the bishop on g7, meaning out of the c3-knight's
range,} 16. h5 g5 17. Qf5 {can be answered with} Bc8 $1 18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19. Nxd5
Bxg4 $17) 16... Qd6 17. h5 g5 18. Rhe1 Rfe8 19. Qd3 Re6 {With two bishops and
the better structure (g4 is always hanging) Black has an excellent play.} 20. Ne2
Rae8 (20... a6 21. Ba4 (21. Bxc6 Bxc6 22. Ng3 Bb5 $15 23. Qd2 $6 Qf4 24. Qxf4
gxf4 25. Nf5 Be2 $17) 21... Rae8 22. Ng3 Rxe1 23. Nxe1 b5 24. Bc2 Bc8 $15) 21.
Ng3 Rxe1 22. Nxe1 {Ashwin,J (2436) -Mijovic,S (2289) Gaziantep 2008 (½-½, 32)
} Qf4 23. Qf5 (23. Nf5 Qxg4) 23... Qxd4 $3 24. Rxd4 Rxe1+ 25. Rd1 Rxd1+ 26. Kc2
Nd4+ 27. Kxd1 Nxf5 28. Nxf5 Kf8 29. b3 Bc8 $15 *

