1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Qc2
Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O c5 12. dxc5 {Since the immediate
attack does not have clear consequences due to Black's pressure on d4, this
move requires a detailed examination. White intends to use his pressure in the
centre to prove the black pawns weak. But Black has enough dynamic resources
due to the control over the long diagonal(s) and of the c-file.} Nd7 $1 {
Not the first time we see this pawn sacrifice.} (12... bxc5 $2 13. Nxd5 Bxd5
14. Bc4) 13. c6 {The positional and safest approach.} (13. cxb6 Bxc3 14. bxc3
axb6 $40 {With the white king exposed, accepting the sacrifice is even more
dangerous than in some previous lines.} 15. Nd4 Nc5 16. Bb5 Qe7 {[%cal Gf8c8,
Gc5e4] followed by ...Rfc8 and ...Ne4.}) (13. Nxd5 {This dubious move has
yielded White a few wins in games between very strong players.} Nxc5 {Black is
better developed and has excellent attacking chances. White's domination in
the centre is only apparent.} 14. Bc4 {This developing move fails to
consolidate White.} (14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $19 {yields Black a decisive advance in
development. White is helpless against ...Rac8 and ...Be4.} 15. Bd3 Rfe8 {
threatening ...Nxd3+ followed by ...Be4.} 16. Nd2 Rac8 17. Kb1 Bxg2 18. Rhg1
Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxf2 $19) (14. Qf5 Bxd5 15. Rxd5 Qe7 {offers Black a simple
attack with opposite coloured bishops.} 16. Kb1 g6 (16... Na4 17. Bd3 g6 18.
Qe4 Qxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxb2 $11 {Myc,M (2245)-Dubiel,J (2395) Biala Podlaska 1994 
(0-1, 28)}) 17. Qf4 Rfd8 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Be2 Kg7 20. Rc1 (20. Rd1 $2 Rxd1+
21. Bxd1 Nd3 $19) 20... Ne4 $15 {planning either ...Nxf2 or ...Nd2.}) 14... b5
$1 15. Nxf6+ (15. Bxb5 Bxd5 16. Bc4 Be4 $19 17. Rxd8 Rfxd8 18. Qe2 Nd3+ 19.
Bxd3 Bxd3 20. Qd2 Rac8+ 21. Kd1 Bc2+) 15... Qxf6 16. Bd5 Rac8 17. Kb1 Na4 18.
Qe2 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Rc4 $1 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gc4b4]} (19... Qg6+ 20. e4 Rc4 21. Ne5
Qxg2 22. Nxc4 Qxh1+ 23. Rd1 Qxh2 24. Nd6 a6 25. Qe3 Qe5 26. Rd2 {Ivkov,B (2485)
-Trifunovic,M (2295) Pozarevac 1995 (1-0, 38)} Nxb2 $1 27. f4 Qf6 28. e5 Nc4 $1
29. Nxc4 Qf5+ $1 $17 {Probably Black missed the combination between the last
two moves.}) 20. Rd4 Rfc8 21. Rhd1 Rc2 $1 {Hard to say why Black refrained
from this obvious move in Kasparov,G (2595)-Zaitsev,I (2190) Baku 1980 (1-0,
30)} 22. Qxc2 (22. R1d2 Rxb2+ 23. Rxb2 Nc3+) (22. Rd8+ Kh7 {only opens the
long diagonal for the queen.}) 22... Rxc2 23. Kxc2 Qg6+ 24. Kd2 Nxb2 25. Rc1
Qxg2 (25... Qe6 $5 {Threatening ... Qxa2.}) 26. Ke2 Nc4 $15 {Ghitescu,
T-Lputian,S/Berlin/ 1982/0:1 (68)}) 13... Bxc6 14. Nd4 Bb7 15. g4 {After
stabilizing the centre, White does not have anything better than switching
back to his main plan.} (15. h4 {should be answered in the same way as in the
main line.} Ne5 $146 16. Be2 Nc6) (15. Kb1 {is rather slow and allows Black to
start a pawn attack himself:} a6 16. g4 b5 17. h4 (17. Bg2 Rc8 18. Qf5 Ne5 19.
e4 Rxc3 20. bxc3 Bc8 21. Qf4 Qa5 22. Qc1 Nc4 $17 {Nikolic,P (2490)-Lputian,S 
(2495) Sarajevo 1983 (0-1, 31)}) 17... b4 18. Na4 {Srokowski,J (2430)-Fancsy,I
(2385) Germany 1999 (1-0, 34)} Rc8 19. Qd2 Bxd4 20. exd4 Bc6 21. Nc5 Nxc5 22.
dxc5 d4 23. Rg1 Be4+ 24. Bd3 Qd5 $11) (15. Be2 {Ubilava,E (2455)-Agzamov,V 
(2255) Yerevan 1981 (0-1, 28)} a6 16. Kb1 b5 $36) 15... Ne5 16. Be2 Nc6 $1 {
Even though this position is mainly about attacking on the opposite wings, the
fight for the centre remains essential.} (16... Rc8 17. h4 Bxh4 $2 18. f4 Ng6
19. Bd3 b5 20. Bxb5 Bf6 21. g5 $1 hxg5 22. Qh2 Nh4 23. fxg5 Bxg5 24. Kb1 $18 {
Zaichik,G-Lputian,S (2495) Jurmala 1983 (1-0, 31)}) 17. Qd2 (17. Ndb5 d4 {
Kharitonov}) (17. Nf3 Nb4 18. Qb3 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Na6 $17 {Kharitonov}) (17. Nxc6
Bxc6 18. Bf3 (18. Ba6 d4) 18... Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Rc8 20. Kb1 d4 21. Rxd4 Bxf3 22.
Rxd8 Rxc3 $19 {Kharitonov}) 17... Nxd4 18. exd4 Re8 $10 19. Kb1 a6 20. f4 b5
21. Bf3 Rc8 22. Qg2 Re3 $1 {Ubilava,E (2445)-Kharitonov,A Tallinn 1983 (0-1,
38)} 23. Bxd5 Rcxc3 24. Bxb7 Rcd3 25. Qd5 Qxd5 26. Bxd5 Rxd4 27. Rxd4 Bxd4 28.
