1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Rc1 $5 {
This move order used to enjoy some popularity a few decades ago. White's main
idea is to switch to the fianchetto after the usual exchanges on d5.} b6 ({
A simpler but less ambitious approach is} 7... dxc4 {One important point is
that after} 8. e3 c5 9. Bxc4 cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {the rook is not best placed
for the Isolani structure (rooks should go to d1 and e1 to ensure White
attacking chances). The game where this plan was first played went} 11. O-O Nh5
12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Bb3 Nf6 {Kortschnoj,V (2650)-Karpov,A (2690) Merano 1981 
(0-1, 43)}) 8. cxd5 ({The alternative is} 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. g3 Be6
$1 {The bishops stand well next to each other.} 11. Bg2 c5 12. O-O Nc6 13. dxc5
(13. e3 Rc8 14. Qa4 {Panno,O-Esposito,A Mar del Plata 1957 (½-½, 57)} cxd4
15. exd4 Qd7 16. Rcd1 Rfd8 $11) 13... bxc5 14. Ne1 Bxc3 (14... Ne7 15. Nd3 Rc8
16. e3 Qa5 17. a3 Rfd8 18. Nf4 c4 19. Qe2 Be5 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Bh3 Rc6 22.
Rfd1 Rb8 $13 {Vaganian, R (2590)-Petrosian, A (2435) Yerevan 1980 (0-1, 41) This
looks okay for Black, but I prefer the main line as having a permanent
weakness on e6 is irritating.}) 15. bxc3 (15. Rxc3 c4 16. e3 Rb8 17. Qd2 d4 18.
Ra3 dxe3 19. Qxe3 Nd4 20. Rxa7 Rxb2 $17 {Rivas Pastor,M (2520)-Kotronias,V 
(2560) Manila 1992 (½-½, 32)}) 15... Ne5 (15... c4 16. Nf3 Qa5 17. Qc2 Rab8
18. Rfd1 Qa3 19. Rb1 Rfd8 $11 {The point is that White has no obvious way of
establishing a blockade on d4:} 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Qxc3 $1 $19 22. Qxc3
Rxb1+ 23. Bf1 Bh3) 16. Nd3 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Rb8 {In the next phase the mutual
weaknesses will keep the chances even.} 18. Rfd1 Rb2 19. Qe3 Rxa2 20. Qxc5 Rxe2
21. Qxa7 Qg5 22. Qd4 Rb8 23. Bf3 (23. Bxd5 $2 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Re1+) 23... Re5 $11
{Geller,E (2565)-Beliavsky,A (2590) Vilnius 1980 (½-½, 25)}) 8... Nxd5 9.
Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. g3 Re8 {If White could get castled properly, he
would keep some chances to put the hanging pawns under pressure by using his
fianchetto bishop. But the pressure on e2 and his slight delay in kingside
development prevent him from achieving that.} 12. Bg2 (12. Rc3 {This rook
lift aims to defend the e-file but it wastes even more developing time.} Na6
13. Qa4 (13. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Ge2]} 14. e3 Nc7 15. O-O Bf5 16. Ne5 Be4 $11) 13...
b5 $5 {A surgical way of using the advance in development.} ({The piece
sacrifice} 13... c5 $2 14. Re3 Be6 15. Qxa6 $16 {was not justified in the
earlier game between the same players, Seirawan, Y (2575)-Karpov, A (2720)
London 1982 (1-0, 31)}) 14. Qa5 (14. Qxb5 Rb8 15. Qa4 Rxb2 $17) 14... Qe4 15.
Kd2 Re6 (15... Bf5 $5 {may be the best way to achieve counterplay.} 16. Qxa6 (
16. Rc1 {defends b1 but allows} Bh3 $1) 16... Qb1 17. Qc6 Qxa2 {[%cal Gb5b4]}
18. Kd1 Qxb2 19. Re3 Qa1+ 20. Qc1 Qa4+ 21. Ke1 Qb4+ 22. Qd2 (22. Nd2 Qxd4 $15)
22... Qb1+ 23. Qd1 Qa2 $5 {Planning ...Bc2 followed by ...b5-b4-b3.} 24. Qb3
Qa5+ 25. Nd2 Qa1+ 26. Qd1 Qxd4 $15 {with three dangerous pawns for the piece.})
16. b3 $2 (16. Re3 {is safer and stronger.} Qb1 17. Qa3 b4 18. Qb3 Rxe3 19.
fxe3 {and White is not without chances in this unusual position.}) 16... b4 17.
Re3 Qb1 {Black has a very strong attack already.} 18. Rxe6 Qb2+ 19. Kd1 Bxe6
20. Qxa6 Qa1+ 21. Kd2 Qc3+ 22. Kd1 Bf5 23. Ne1 Rb8 24. Qxa7 Rb6 25. e3 Rc6 26.
Bc4 Qa1+ 27. Ke2 Qb2+ 28. Kd1 dxc4 29. Qa8+ Kh7 30. Qxc6 c3 {0-1 Seirawan, Y 
(2575)-Karpov,A (2720) Hamburg (rapid) 1982. Karpov seems to have been so
proud for equalizing the personal score with Seirawan (after a few games in
which he mainly struggled with white) that in his comments about his 100 best
games he forgot to mention that this was a rapid game.}) 12... Ba6 {This is
just natural. Black should cause his opponent problems with getting castled.} (
12... c5 {is sound, but likely to leave White with some pressure:} 13. O-O Bb7
14. e3 Nd7 15. Qa4 Nf6 16. Nd2 {Kharitonov,A (2450)-Pigusov,E (2520) Sochi
1987 (½-½, 27)}) 13. e3 (13. Ne5 {allows the spectacular} Nd7 $1 {with
strong counterplay.} 14. f4 {The most solid.} (14. Rxc7 Rac8 $1 15. Rxd7 (15.
Rxc8 Rxc8 16. O-O Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Re1 d4 $5 {With at last equal play
for Black, Uhlmann,W-Veresov, G Schwedt 1969 (0-1, 41)}) 15... Qb4+ 16. Kf1
Qxd4 17. Nd3 Rxe2 18. Kxe2 Re8+ $5 (18... Bxd3+ 19. Qxd3 Re8+ 20. Kd2 Qxb2+ {
leads to a perpetual.}) 19. Kf1 Qxd3+ 20. Qxd3 Bxd3+ 21. Kg1 Re1+ 22. Bf1 Bxf1
23. Rd8+ {Removing the rook from the light square in order to avoid a deadly
discovered check.} Kh7 24. h4 Bd3+ 25. Kh2 Re2 $44) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Rad8 $1
(15... Bb7 {requires a longer defensive effort from Black:} 16. O-O Red8 17. b4
c6 18. Qb3 Rac8 19. Rfd1 Ba6 20. Qb2 Bb5 21. Rd2 Ra8 22. e4 dxe4 23. Bxe4 Rxd2
24. Qxd2 Rd8 25. Qc3 Qe6 26. a3 g6 {Uhlmann,W (2475)-Kurajica,B (2495)
Sarajevo 1981 (½-½, 41)}) 16. Qa4 (16. O-O Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 17. b4 $6
f6 $15) 16... Bc8 17. Qxa7 (17. Rd1 Be6 18. Qc6 f6 $5 $11) (17. O-O c5 $15)
17... Qb4+ 18. Kf2 Qd4+ 19. Kf1 Qxb2 20. Qxc7 d4 (20... f6 $5 $11) 21. Qc2 Qa3
$44) 13... c5 14. Qa4 Rc8 (14... Qd7 {may be not entirely satisfactory:} 15.
Qxd7 Nxd7 $11 16. Kd2 (16. Bh3 Rad8 17. Bxd7 Rxd7 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Rxc5 d4 20.
Ne5 Rb7 21. b3 dxe3 22. fxe3 Rbe7 $15) 16... Nf6 17. Rhd1 Rac8 18. Ne5 Ne4+ 19.
Ke1 {and White has managed to regroup properly.}) ({But since in a line below
I recommend ...Rc8-d8,} 14... Rd8 {deserves mentioning.} 15. Ne5 Qe6 16. Rc3
Rd6) 15. Ne5 Qe6 16. Rc3 {White cannot castle yet but Black faces problems
