1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Rb1 {
A few decades ago, Kevin Spraggett displayed his enthusiasm towards this move,
apparently an invention of the Portuguese players. The main idea is that
unlike in the 8.Be2 line, Black cannot meet the later b2-b4 with ...c7-c5. But
since we do not play that against 8.Be2 anyway, the early rook move is more of
a commitment.} (8. g4 {is not entirely justified aggression.} Nbd7 9. Rg1 Bb7
10. g5 (10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. g5 hxg5 12. Nxg5 dxc4 13. Qc2 c5 14. O-O-O Qc7 15.
Bh3 Qxh2 16. Rg3 Bd6 17. Nf3 Bxf3 18. Rxf3 cxd4 19. exd4 Bf4+ 20. Kb1 Bh6 $17 {
Kanep,M (2531)-Kiuttu,R (2283) Jyvaskyla 2011 (½-½, 33)}) 10... Ne4 11. cxd5
exd5 12. Bh3 (12. Bb5 c6 13. Bd3 c5 $17) 12... g6 (12... Nxg5 $2 13. Nxg5 hxg5
14. Qh5 $40 {Javakhishvili,L (2487)-Koneru,H (2575) Chengdu 2016 (½-½, 31)})
13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. gxh6 Bxh4 15. Nxh4 Kh7 $1 (15... Qh3 $2 16. Qh5 Nxf2 17.
Rxg6+ Kh8 18. Rg3 Nd3+ 19. Kd2 {1-0 Shabalov,A (2591)-Amanov,Z (2394) Las
Vegas 2010}) 16. Nf3 f6 $15 {White's attack is over and Black keeps the
control in the centre and is better developed, too.}) (8. Bxf6 {is premature
before Black has developed his queen's bishop. For instance} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5
10. Qb3 Be6 11. Rd1 Qc8 $5 $146 {slowly preparing ...c7-c5 when the queen will
be exposed on b3.} 12. Be2 (12. Nxd5 $2 Bd8 {wins the knight soon for instance}
13. Bc4 b5) 12... Rd8 13. O-O c5 $15) 8... Bb7 9. Bxf6 (9. b4 {is somewhat
premature.} Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxe4 (11. Qc2 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 c5 $15) 11...
dxe4 12. Nd2 (12. Ne5 $6 Kh7 13. Qg4 Qe8 {puts the knight in danger in view of
...f7-f6.}) 12... a5 13. a3 (13. b5 e5 {using the relative weakness on c5.})
13... axb4 14. axb4 Nd7 15. Be2 Ra2 {with excellent counterplay.}) 9... Bxf6
10. cxd5 (10. b4 {offers Black a choice} dxc4 (10... c6 $5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Ga7a5]}
11. cxd5 cxd5 $5) 11. Bxc4 Qc8 12. Qb3 Nd7 13. O-O (13. Be2 c5 14. bxc5 Rb8 $11
15. cxb6 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Rxb6 17. Bb5 Qc7 $36) 13... c5 14. Be2 {½-½ Krasenkow,
M (2573)-Lugovoi,A (2485) Panormo 2001} cxd4 15. exd4 Qd8 $15) 10... exd5 11.
b4 c6 {Everything along familiar patterns. As mentioned before, Rb1 is not an
improvment of White's position at this height of the game.} 12. Qb3 Re8 13. Be2
Nd7 14. O-O Nf8 15. Rfd1 Ne6 16. Bf1 (16. b5 c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qb4 Ne6 19.
Ne4 (19. Qb3 d4) 19... Be7 20. Qb3 Rc8 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22. Rxd4 Bc5 23. Nxc5 bxc5
$132) 16... Qd6 17. g3 Rad8 18. Bg2 g6 19. Rd2 Bg7 20. Qd1 Nc7 21. a4 Bc8 22.
Ne1 Bf5 ({The careless} 22... h5 {allows} 23. b5 $14 {Ivanisevic,I (2460)
-Sturua,Z (2595) Yerevan 2000 (1-0, 49)}) 23. Nd3 (23. Rbb2 c5 24. bxc5 bxc5
