1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 {This is
another important group of variations. White immediately exchanges his bishop,
aiming at speeding up his development and keeping the control in the centre.
Black cannot seriously think of playing ...b7-b6 anymore as this would
practically waste a tempo with respect to the normal Tartakower lines. But
against most white setups the bishop proves very strong after ...c7-c5 which
frequently implies a pawn sacrifice.} 7. e3 {This is the main move order.
White has several alternatives, but in all lines, he is best adviced to
transpose to the normal system with a later e2-e3.} (7. Qb3 c5 8. dxc5 O-O 9.
O-O-O (9. Qa3 dxc4 10. e3 Nd7 11. Bxc4 Qc7) (9. cxd5 {Bu,X (2662)-Negi,P (2622)
Mashhad 2011 (1-0, 50)} exd5 10. Nxd5 Bxb2 11. Qxb2 Qxd5 12. Rc1 Be6 13. a3 Nd7
) 9... Nd7 10. cxd5 Nxc5 11. Qb5 b6 12. dxe6 Qe7 13. Nd4 (13. exf7+ Qxf7 14. e3
Ba6 15. Qb4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bxf1 17. Rhxf1 Qxa2 18. Qb2 Qe6 $17) 13... Bxe6 14.
Kb1 {Araslanov,F (2310)-Korneev,O (2500) Badalona 1994 (0-1, 27)} a6 15. Qb4 a5
16. Qa3 Bxd4 17. Rxd4 Rfd8 $19) (7. e4 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nc6 9. d5 {This was played
by a few very strong players, but is rather risky.} (9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Qd2 {
is safer but does not face Black with problems.} O-O 11. Qe3 Rd8 12. O-O-O b6
13. Bd3 Bb7 14. Be4 Rab8 15. Rd2 {Bisguier,A-Moskowitz,J Los Angeles 1954 (1-0,
56)} Na5 16. Ne5 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 b5 18. c5 Nc4 19. Nxc4 bxc4 $132) 9... Ne5 10.
Be2 (10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Qe2 {Nikolic,P (2485)-Tal,M (2605) Wijk
aan Zee 1982 (½-½, 18)} Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 exd5 14. cxd5 Ke7 15. Rc1 Kd6 $15)
10... O-O 11. Qb3 exd5 12. cxd5 c6 13. Rd1 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Qa5+ 15. Rd2 Re8 $17
{Romanishin,O (2610)-Geller,E (2590) Tbilisi 1978 (0-1, 59)}) ({Another way of
carrying out the opening of the centre is} 7. Qd2 O-O 8. e4 (8. O-O-O $2 $146
c5 $15 9. dxc5 Nd7 10. cxd5 Nxc5 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Qxd8 Rfxd8 13. Rxd8+ Rxd8
$17) 8... c5 9. cxd5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 exd5 11. exd5 (11. Nxd5 Re8 12. O-O-O Rxe4
$11) 11... Nc6 $5 (11... Nd7 12. Be2 Nb6 $11) 12. Nc2 (12. dxc6 Qxd4 13. Qxd4
Bxd4 $15) (12. Nxc6 bxc6 $15 13. dxc6 $2 Re8+ 14. Be2 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Ba6 $19)
12... Ne7 (12... Re8+ 13. Ne3 Nd4 14. Bd3 Nf5 15. Bxf5 Bxf5 16. O-O $14 {
Tukmakov,V (2570)-Speelman,J (2530) Moscow 1985 (1-0, 41)}) 13. Ne3 Nf5 14. Bd3
(14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Be2 Qb6 16. O-O Bg5 17. Qd1 Qxb2 18. Bd3 Qxc3 19. Bxf5 Rad8
$11 20. d6 $2 Qf6 $17) 14... Nxe3 15. fxe3 Be5 $44 {with fantastic play on the
dark squares.}) ({If} 7. cxd5 exd5 {White does not have anything better than
to transpose to the lines below with e2-e3.} 8. g3 $6 {It is known that in the
Karlsbad structure the bishop does not belong on g2 as it hits a wall and
fails to sustain b4-b5 or control c4.} (8. b4 c6) 8... O-O 9. Bg2 c6 10. O-O
Bf5 11. e3 Nd7 12. Nd2 Nb6 13. Rc1 a5 (13... Re8 14. Re1 Nc8 15. Nb3 Nd6) 14.
Re1 Re8 15. Nb3 Nc4 16. e4 {Otherwise ...Nd6.} dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxb2 18. Qd2 Bxe4
19. Rxe4 Rxe4 20. Bxe4 Na4 {White still has to prove his compensation for the
pawn.Maghsoodloo,P (2416)-Zhou,J (2600) Al Ain 2015 (0-1, 60)}) 7... O-O 8. Qd2
{This is a solid move, but the queen is not especially active here. Besides,
after the opening of the d-file, the queen exchange would annihilate one of
White's developing tempi.} (8. cxd5 exd5 {leads to a comfortable version of
the exchange variation. In the absence of the white dark-squared bishop Black
enjoys more freedom. More about this structure in the second strategic article.
} 9. Bd3 (9. Rc1 c6 10. Bd3 Bg4 $5) 9... c5 $5 10. dxc5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nd7 $11)
({In the next lines we will cover} 8. Qc2) (8. Qb3 {and}) (8. Rc1) 8... c5 {
The most resolute move.} ({Black could also play in the spirit of line 16 with
} 8... Nc6 9. O-O-O (9. Rc1 {transposes to line 16.}) (9. Be2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5
11. d5 Ne7) 9... a6 10. h4 dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. d5 Na7 $5 {planning ...Nb5
Braunberger,F-Wagman,S (2215) Mendrisio 1988 (0-1, 40)}) 9. cxd5 {The most
consistent.} (9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd2+ {is the aforementioned situation
when Qd2 proves to be a waste of time.} 11. Nxd2 Nd7 12. Nde4 Be7 13. c6 (13.
b4 a5) 13... bxc6 14. O-O Nb6 15. Be2 e5 16. Rfd1 Be6) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 exd5
11. Bb5 $1 {Aimed at preventing ...Nc6 which would shake White's central
stability. In many lines with a similar structure, the knight goes all the way
to e6 to attack d4.} Nc6 $1 $146 {Nevertheless possible! Black obtains very
strong compensation for the pawn as the enemy king is still in the centre.} (
11... Qd6 12. Rc1 $1 (12. O-O Rd8 13. Rfd1 Nc6 14. Nf3 Be6 15. Be2 a6 $15 {
Ubilava,E (2470)-Geller,E (2560) Sochi 1984 (½-½, 31)}) 12... Rd8 (12... Nc6
$2 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ne4 $16) (12... Nd7 13. Nde2 $14) 13. O-O Nc6 (13... Nd7
$5 14. Rfd1 Nb6) 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Na4 Bd7 16. Nc5 $14 {with a safe blockade
in the centre, Agzamov,G-Geller,E (2560) Sochi 1984 (1-0, 41)}) 12. Bxc6 (12.
Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Bxd5 (14. O-O d4 {is likely to lead to a draw as
Black would soon retrieve the pawn on the queenside.}) 14... Ba6 15. Bb3 Bxc3
16. bxc3 Qg5 17. O-O-O Rfc8 $44 {with excellent attacking chances.}) 12... bxc6
13. Nxc6 ({White has no time to switch to the blockade.} 13. Na4 Ba6 14. Nc5
Bc4 15. b3 Qe7 16. Na4 c5 $17) (13. O-O c5 14. Nb3 c4 15. Nd4 Re8 {is very
pleasant for Black due to his two bishops. He even has chances for a kingside
attack based on a rook lift.}) 13... Qe8 14. Nd4 Ba6 15. Nxd5 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Rc8
17. Nc3 Qe7 $5 18. Rd1 (18. O-O-O $2 Rxc3+ 19. bxc3 Qa3+ 20. Kc2 Qxa2+ 21. Kc1
Rb8) (18. Qa4 Qd6 19. Rd1 Qg6 20. g3 Rfd8 $44) 18... Qb7 {attacking b2 and g2
with obvious compensation for the remaining pawn.} 19. Rd2 Qxg2 20. Qd5 Qxd5
21. Nxd5 Rc1+ 22. Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Kxd1 Rd8 24. e4 Bc4 $11 *

