1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1
{This is the most solid move and the main line at the same time. White
over-defends c3 in order to inhibit ...c7-c5. At the same time, he invites his
opponent to display his cards without exposing the queen in any way.} Nc6 $5 {
I like the plan introduced by this move as it leads to playing with chances for
both sides. The main idea is to counterattack in the centre with ...dxc4
followed by ...e6-e5 aiming for a safe blockade on d6.} ({The main line goes} 
8... c6 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. h3 exd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bb3 {
when Black is basically fine but generally speaking this looks like a
favourable version of the French Isolani (with reversed colours) and lasting
pressure for White.}) 9. a3 ({Even with the knight on c6 the exchange is not
too effective:} 9. cxd5 exd5 {The point is that Black has the regrouping ...
Ne7-f5-d6, with perfect stability in the centre.} 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 $5 {leaves
the d3-square available for the king's knight.} Ne7 11. O-O {Boensch,U (2450)
-Gruenberg,H (2450) Cottbus 1983 (1-0, 41)} c6 $1 {Black probably did not
anticipate White's plan and delayed his regrouping a bit which resulted in a
worse position.} 12. b4 a6 13. Ne1 Nf5 14. Nd3 Nd6 15. a4 b5 $5 $11) 10... Ne7
11. b4 c6 12. b5 (12. O-O Be6 13. a4 a6 14. Qb3 Qd6 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 Qa3 $5
{With ...c6-c5 in the air Black has good counterplay.}) 12... cxb5 $1 13. Bxb5
a6 14. Be2 b5 15. Nd2 Be6 16. Nb3 Nf5 17. O-O Be7 18. g3 Rc8 19. Bf3 (19. Bd3
Ba3 20. Rc2 Qd6 21. Qf3 Ne7 $11) 19... Ba3 20. Rc2 Qc7 (20... Qd6 $15) 21. Na1
Qd7 $15 {Shneider,A (2460)-Petrosian,A (2470) Sverdlovsk 1984 (0-1, 41)}) (9.
Be2 {allows Black to display the main plan at once.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5 11. d5
Ne7 12. Ne4 Nf5 (12... Ng6 $5 {planning ...Be7-d6 is a worthy though less
popular alternative.} 13. d6 $5 cxd6 14. Qxd6 Qxd6 15. Nxd6 e4 16. Nxe4 Bxb2
17. Rb1 Ba3 18. Rb3 Be7 19. Ke2 Rd8 20. h4 b5 21. Bxb5 Be6 22. h5 Rab8 23. Ba6
Bxb3 24. axb3 Nf8 $15 {Salov,V-Lechtynsky,J (2470) Stary Smokovec 1984 (½-½,
75)}) 13. O-O (13. Be2 Be7 14. O-O Nd6 15. Ng3 {½-½ Portisch,L (2625)
-Campora,D (2480) Amsterdam 1984}) 13... Nd6 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Be2 {
Dzindzichashvili,R (2560)-Christiansen,L (2595) Jacksonville 1990 (½-½, 32)}
e4 16. Nd4 Qg5 17. Kh1 Qxd5 18. Rxc7 Qxa2 19. Qd2 Qd5 {White may have
compensation for the pawn but Black has no reasons for worrying.}) (9. Qd2 a6 {
Black plays a useful move waiting for White to waste a tempo with his bishop.}
10. Be2 (10. a3 $6 Na5 11. Nxd5 Nb3 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Qc3 Nxc1 14. Qxc1 c5 $15
{Bagaturov,G (2478)-Jojua,D (2420) Tbilisi 2007 (½-½, 17)}) 10... dxc4 11.
Bxc4 e5 12. d5 Na7 $5 {Under the given circumstances this is a good
alternative to the retreat to e7. Since the pawn on a2 is slightly hanging,
Black threatens ...Nb5.} 13. Qc2 (13. O-O Bg4 14. Be2 Nb5 15. Ne4 Be7 16. h3
Bxf3 17. Bxf3 f5 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 {Gurevich, D (2475)-Greenfeld, A (2505)
Beersheba 1986 (1-0, 40)} e4 20. Be2 Nd6 21. Rfc1 Rf7 22. Qc3 Rc8 $11 {With
such a knight on d6 Black is not worse for sure.}) 13... Nb5 14. Nxb5 axb5 15.
Bb3 e4 16. Nd4 Bxd4 17. exd4 c6 18. dxc6 Qxd4 19. O-O bxc6 20. Qxc6 Bd7 21. Qd5
Qxd5 22. Bxd5 Ra6 23. Rfd1 Be6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (44) Karpov,A (2700)-Kasparov,G 
(2710) Moscow 1984}) 9... a6 10. Bd3 (10. b4 {does not really improve White's
position after} dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. d5 Ne7 13. Ne4 Nf5 14. Bb3 Nd6 15. Nxf6+ {
½-½ Kouatly,B (2450)-Santo Roman,M (2435) Royan 1988} Qxf6 $1 $11 16. Rxc7 (
16. h3 e4 17. Nd4 Qg5 18. g4 Qe7 $11 19. Qc2 Bd7 $15) 16... Bg4 17. h3 Bh5 18.
g4 Bg6 19. O-O Rac8 $15 {The knight is very strong, stabilizing Black's
position, while White is exposed on the kingside.}) (10. cxd5 exd5 {The move ..
.a7-a6 is more useful than a2-a3 from the point of view of the minority's
attack.} 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. h3 c6 13. Qb3 g6 14. O-O Bg7 15. Na4 Rb8 16. Qb6 Bf5
17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Be2 Nc8 19. Nc5 Nd6 {The dream square for the knight.} 20.
Nd2 Re8 21. Bg4 Bc8 22. Nd3 Re7 23. Bxc8 Rxc8 24. g4 f6 25. Kg2 Kf7 26. Rh1 Rh8
27. Nf4 h5 $5 28. gxh5 gxh5 29. Kf3 Bh6 $11 {Volke,K (2455)-Vaganian,R (2640)
Germany 1997 (½-½, 45)}) (10. h3 Re8 11. Qc2 $6 {Harika,D (2514)-Melia,S 
(2403) Caleta 2013 (½-½, 45)} e5 $1 $146 12. dxe5 (12. cxd5 exd4 13. Ne4 Qxd5
14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bc4 Qf5 16. Qb3 Qg6 $15) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. cxd5
Qg5 $11 15. Rd1 Bf5 16. Qd2 Rad8 {with huge compensation for the pawn.}) 10...
dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. d5 (12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxf7+ {leads only to
a draw by perpetual} Kxf7 15. Qh5+ Ke6 16. Qg4+ Kf7 $11) 12... Ne7 (12... Na7 {
makes less sense with the white a-pawn defended by his colleague.}) 13. Ne4 Nf5
(13... Ng6 $5 $146 14. Nxf6+ (14. O-O Be7 {[%cal Ge7d6] followed by ...Bd6.})
14... Qxf6 15. Nd2 Bf5 16. e4 Bd7 $11) 14. Be2 (14. Ba2 Nd6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16.
Rxc7 (16. O-O Bg4 $1) 16... e4 17. Nd4 Qg5 18. g3 Bh3 $44) (14. Qc2 Nd6 (14...
Bd7 15. Bd3 Rc8 {is also possible.}) 15. Bd3 Bf5 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Bxf5 Nxf5
18. e4 (18. Qxc7 e4 19. Ne5 Nh4 20. O-O Qg5 21. g3 Qxe5 22. gxh4 Qxd5 $15)
18... Nd6 19. O-O Rac8 $11 {Black will soon start his kingside play with ...
f7-f5.}) 14... Nd6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. O-O (16. Rxc7 e4 17. Nd4 Qg5 18. g3 Qxd5
19. Qc2 (19. O-O Bh3 20. Re1 Rac8 $15) 19... Bh3 20. Bf1 Bg4 21. h3 Rac8 $1 (
21... Bf3 $5) 22. hxg4 Rxc7 23. Qxc7 Rc8 24. Qe7 (24. Qb6 Rc1+ 25. Ke2 $1 $11)
(24. Qd7 Rc1+ 25. Ke2 Qa2 $19) 24... Rc1+ 25. Kd2 Rb1 $44) 16... Bg4 $5 (16...
e4 17. Nd4 $14 {Heyken,E (2415)-Boensch,U (2510) Germany 1990 (½-½, 45)}) 17.
