1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bf4 $5 {Apparently a loss
of time, this move intends to prove that ...h7-h6 is a weakening move if
compared to the 6.Bf4 lines (examined in the second database). Black's task is
to find precisely a system in which .. h7-h6 is useful!} O-O 7. e3 c5 {Against
6.Bf4 this plan leaves Black struggling for equality in long forced lines.
With ...h7-h6 on board things are easier for him,.} ({The main problem with} 
7... b6 {examined against 6.Bf4 (and also of 7...Nbd7) is} 8. g4 {followed by
either h2-h4 or g4-g5, when the pawn on h6 is a target. The positions are not
entirely clear but I would not like to expose the king. If} Nxg4 $2 9. Rg1 h5 (
9... f5 10. h3 Nf6 11. Bxh6) 10. h3 Nf6 11. Ne5 {with an overwhelming attack.})
8. dxc5 (8. Bd3 {offers Black a comfortable version of the white Isolani.} cxd4
9. exd4 (9. Nxd4 Nbd7 10. Bg3 Nc5 $11) 9... Nc6 10. O-O (10. a3 dxc4 11. Bxc4
b6 12. O-O Bb7 {White cannot prepare the attack based on Qd2, Bd3 and Bxh6
easily, for instance} 13. Qd2 Na5 14. Ba2 {Defending b3.} Rc8) 10... Nb4 11.
Be2 (11. c5 b6 12. Bb5 bxc5 13. a3 Na6 14. Bc6 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Rb8 16. Bxb8 Nxb8
17. Re1 Bc5 {with at least enough compensation for the exchange due to the
bishops' pair and the strong centre.}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 {This is a
theoretical position in which White is to move. Black can use the extra tempo
with} b6) (8. g4 $2 {makes no sense with the centre under tension already.}
cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. g5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Re8) 8... Bxc5 9. a3 {One of the main
plans after 6.Bf4.} (9. Rc1 Nc6 10. Be2 {allows Black to equalize effortlessly
.} dxc4 11. Bxc4 Qe7 {The first moment when ...h7-h6 is useful, as Black
threatens ...e6-e5 without fearing Bg5.} 12. Ne5 Rd8 13. Qe2 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bd7
$11) ({The other typical main plan} 9. cxd5 {is examined in Line 18.}) 9... Nc6
10. Qc2 {Following the familiar paths from the 6.Bf4 system.} ({If} 10. b4 {
from all the playable retreats I prefer} Bb6 $146 11. Be2 (11. c5 {leaves
Black with a mobile centre.} Bc7 12. Bxc7 Qxc7 13. Be2 Rd8 14. Nb5 Qe7 15. Nd6
e5 $11 {possibly followed by ...Ne8.}) (11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 {does not
improve over Line 18.}) 11... Nh5 $5 {Another moment when the control over g5
is important.} 12. cxd5 Nxf4 13. exf4 Qf6 14. Rc1 (14. O-O Nxb4 $5 15. axb4
Qxc3 16. d6 Bd7) (14. Qd2 exd5 15. O-O Be6 {with at least equality.}) 14... Rd8
15. Qd2 Ne7 16. d6 Nd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Qxd5 Qxf4 19. Rd1 Bc7 {After
retrieving the pawn Black will have two active bishops.}) 10... Qe7 $1 {
This move, played in a very old game, seems the best to me. As in a line above,
Black threatens ...e6-e5, something which would not be possible after 6.Bf4 as
White could meet the central expansion with Bg5.} 11. cxd5 (11. b4 Bb6 (11...
d4 $2 12. bxc5 e5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 $18 {Ruppel,L (2270)-Dianda,J Sao
Paulo 1995 (1-0, 28)}) 12. c5 e5 13. Bg3 (13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. cxb6 d4 $1 {
offers Black strong initiative against the uncastled king.}) 13... Bc7 14. Rd1
Be6 $11) (11. Bg3 $5 $146 d4 (11... Rd8 {is also possible.}) 12. exd4 Nxd4 13.
Nxd4 Bxd4 14. O-O-O e5 15. Nb5 Bb6 16. Bd3 a6 17. Nc3 Bd4 18. Rhe1 Be6 19. Bxe5
Bxe5 20. Rxe5 Qc7 $11) 11... exd5 {Partly due to ... h7-h6, the bishop is not
optimally placed on f4, leaving Black with a comfortable Isolani position.} 12.
Be2 {Belavenets,S-Schneiderman Stepanov,G Moscow 1936 (1-0, 40)} Bg4 (12... Rd8
13. O-O d4 14. exd4 Bxd4 $11) 13. O-O Rad8 {Black is perfectly regrouped and...
.d5-d4 (equalizing or even taking over the initiative) is in the air.} *

