1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bf4 $5 O-O 7. e3 c5 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 9. cxd5 {Another popular plan after 6.Bf4.} Nxd5 ({With g5 defended,
Black could actually keep the knight on board with} 9... exd5 10. Be2 Nc6 11.
O-O Be6 $11) 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 ({Without ...h7-h6} 11. a3 {is the main
move, but here it proves too slow.} Nc6 12. Bd3 (12. Rc1 Bb6 13. Bd3 Qf6 $1
$146 14. b4 d4 $15) 12... Qf6 $1 {The point is that White does not have the
double attack Qc2 or Bxh7+ followed by Qc2+. Besides, the queen is safe on f6,
as it does not have to fear Bg5 or Ng5.} 13. b4 Bb6 14. b5 Qc3+ ({If Black is
content with easy equality he can play} 14... Nd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 $11) 15. Ke2
Na5 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Nxd2 Bg4+ $1 {Inducing the weakening of the e3-square.}
18. f3 g5 19. Bg3 (19. Bxg5 hxg5 20. fxg4 Rae8) 19... Bd7 20. Bf2 Rae8 21. g4
f5 {with strong counterplay.}) (11. Be2 {is worse than the main move as in the
next sub-line the d-pawn is not blocked.} Bb4+ 12. Kf1 (12. Nd2 Nc6 13. O-O d4
$1) 12... Nc6 13. Qb3 Be6 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. Qd3 Rac8 16. h4 Rfd8 17. a3 Bc5 18.
Nd4 Nxd4 19. exd4 Bd6 20. Be3 Qd7 $17 {Gereben,E-Marovic,D Amsterdam 1967 (0-1,
71)}) 11... Bb4+ 12. Ke2 (12. Nd2 $146 {requires certain accuracy.} Nc6 (12...
d4 13. e4 Na6 {This was successful for Black in the lines without ...h7-h6.}
14. O-O Nc5 15. Nb3 Be6 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 {But here I would fear that after e4-e5
the kingside would be a bit vulnerable.}) 13. O-O Qf6 14. a3 Ba5 15. b4 Bb6 16.
Rc1 Bf5 $11) 12... Nc6 13. Bc2 {This principled attempt to take advantage of
the weakness on h6 neglects the development.} ({But Black also has excellent
play after} 13. a3 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qa4 (15. Re1 Bg4 16. Kf1 Bxf3 17. Qxf3
Qxh2 $15) (15. h3 Qf6 16. b4 Rd8 17. b5 Ne5 18. Nd4 Rd6 $15 {Black plans ...
Bd7 followed by ... Re8. White's king is stuck in the centre as if} 19. Re1 Qg5
{with a strong attack.}) 15... Qf6 16. Rab1 Re8 17. Rhe1 d4 $15 18. e4 $2 Bg4
$19) 13... Re8 14. Qd3 g6 $1 {Taking over the initiative at the cost of an
unimportant pawn.} 15. Bxh6 (15. Rhd1 Bf5 16. Qb3 Be6 $15) 15... Bg4 16. a3 (
16. Bf4 d4 17. e4 Bd6 {Playing for the dark squares.} 18. Bg3 (18. Bxd6 Qxd6 {
Threatens ...Ne5.}) 18... Nb4 19. Qd2 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 Bd7 {Threatening ...Bb5.}
21. a4 Bc6 22. Nd2 Bb4 {with strong initiative.}) (16. Kf1 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qh4
18. Bf4 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 Rad8 {with at least sufficient compensation for the pawn
as White is partly paralyzed.}) 16... Ne5 17. Qd4 Bc5 $1 18. Qf4 (18. Qxc5 Rc8
$19) 18... Qb6 19. b4 Qa6+ 20. Kd2 Bd6 21. Qf6 {0-1 Cifuentes Parada,R (2515)
-Piket,J (2640) Rotterdam 1997} Bxb4+ $1 {wins the queen.} *

