{What is the reason why White's previous move was careless?} 13... Rd8 $1 {
This strong move keeps the pawn on d5 and makes the central break unavoidable.}
(13... Nc6 $2 {This is one of the exceptions when the most natural developing
move does not work. The point is that Black does not keep his d5-pawn.} 14.
Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Rac8 16. Be2 $5 $16 {Overdefending the rook in anticipation
of ...Rfd8. Black has no compensation for the pawn.}) (13... Bxc3 $6 {This is
safe, but it does not offer more than equality. It might have been the move
White was counting on.} 14. Qxc3 bxc5 15. Bg2 $11 {Due to the weakness of the
long diagonal Black is not prepared for} d4 16. exd4 Bb3+ (16... Bh3+ 17. Kf1)
17. Qe3 Qxe3+ 18. fxe3 Bxd1 19. Ne5) 14. cxb6 (14. Bg2 {allows} bxc5 15. O-O
Nc6 $17 {with a crushing pressure in the centre.}) (14. c6 {only speeds up
Black's development after} Nxc6 {[%cal Gd5d4]}) 14... d4 $1 15. Bg2 (15. Ne4 {
is another interesting line.} Bd5 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qxd4 {You are invited to
find the win for Black in the next test.}) 15... Nc6 (15... dxc3 $2 16. Qxd8+
Qxd8 17. Rxd8+ Bxd8 18. b7 $18) 16. Nxd4 (16. exd4 Bb3+ 17. Qe2 Bxd1 18. Qxe7
Nxe7 19. Kxd1 axb6 $15) 16... Nxd4 17. exd4 (17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. exd4 Bd5+ 19.
Qe2 Bxh1 20. Qxe7 Bxe7 21. bxa7 $17) 17... Bh3+ (17... Bb3+ 18. Qe2 Bxd1 19.
Qxe7 Bxe7 20. Bxa8 $18) 18. Kf1 Rxd4 {Black has strong initiative and White
cannot complete his kingside regrouping.} *

