{White displayed some early kingside activity. Which is Black's most accurate
plan?} 23... Bh6 $1 {Black needs to maintain his stability on the light
squares at any cost.} 24. f4 {Threatening f4-f5.} Ng7 {The continuation of the
same policy. The blockade has to be extended to the f5-square, too.} (24...
Bxg5 25. hxg5 Ng7 {is similar, but at this height, Black does not need to take
on g5 yet.}) 25. Kf2 {Planning to reinforce the control over the dark (and
indirectly light) squares with Ng1-f3.} (25. e6 {is worth mentioning. You will
have the occasion to find the best defence for Black in the next test.}) 25...
Bxg5 {Now is a good moment to exchange the knight in order to continue
regrouping on light squares.} (25... c5 $2 {was played in Bukic, E (2480)
-Ivanovic,B (2490) Borovo 1981 (0-1, 44). White missed the strongest
continuation but you have the occasion to do better in the next test.}) (25...
Rad8 {This move, completing the development and planning the same regrouping
as in the main line is also very good.} 26. Ng1 Bxg5 27. hxg5 Bc8) 26. hxg5 Bc8
{Black will soon have a firm blockade on several squares along the h3-c8
diagonal.} 27. Ng1 Qb7 (27... h4 $5 {The counterplay initiated by this move is
also promising.} 28. gxh4 Qg4 29. Nf3 Bf5 30. Rg1 Qh5 {with active black play.}
) 28. Nf3 Bg4 {Black has reached absolute stability and can think of preparing
...c6-c5 with ...Ra/ed8.} *

