{Which is the best way to make use of Black's poor coordination induced by the
strange queen retreat to c8?} 28. e6 $1 {Once again, the main theme is the
fight for and against the blockade.} (28. Rc1 $6 {was the game continuation.}
Bf8 (28... Bxg5 $14) 29. Rg1 (29. e6 $1) 29... Nh6 30. Nh2 {Now was a good
moment to retrieve the lost coordination with 30...Qd7 but Black played} Bc6 {
hoping for ...Bd7 Bukic, E (2480)-Ivanovic, B (2490) Borovo 1981 (0-1, 44) In
the next test you will once again have the occasion to make use of Black's
incomplete coordination.}) 28... f6 {Trying to avoid a blockade on dark
squares.} (28... fxe6 29. Bxf5 gxf5 (29... exf5 30. Rxe8+ Qxe8 31. Re1 Qd7 32.
Re6 $18) 30. Ne5 {Planning Qe2xh5.} Ba6 (30... Re7 31. Ng6 $18) 31. Rc1 $18 {
followed by Qd1xh5.}) 29. Bxf5 $1 (29. Nf7 $6 {is not convincing after} Bf8)
29... gxf5 30. Qd3 $1 {A strong piece sacrifice, taking advantage of the fact
that several black pieces are far from the kingside.} (30. Qc2 {may transpose.}
) 30... fxg5 31. Qxf5 Re7 32. Qg6+ Bg7 33. f5 {Threatening f5-f6 or hxg5.} Qe8
34. Qxg5 Qf8 35. Ne5 Qf6 36. Kg2 $1 {Parrying ...Rxe6 and threatening Qxh5.}
Qxg5 37. hxg5 Bxe5 38. Rxe5 Rae8 {Desperately trying to prevent f5-f6.} 39.
Rde1 Bc8 40. f6 $5 (40. Kh3 {is also very strong} cxd4 41. Kh4 $18) 40... Rxe6
41. g6 Kf8 42. Rxh5 Rxf6 43. Rh8+ *

