{How can White use Black's insufficient control on the light squares?} 31. g4
$1 {As usual, pawn breaks are effective ways of fighting against the blockade.}
(31. Qd3 $1 {is also very strong. But from a practical point of view, it is not
easy to evaluate the consequences of the following variation:} Nf5 (31... Bd7
32. Nxf7 $1) (31... Ng4+ 32. Kg2 $1 c4 33. Qf3 Bd7 34. f5 Bxf5 35. Nxg4 hxg4
36. Qxd5 $16) 32. g4 c4 33. Qd2 Nxd4 34. gxh5 Bc5 35. Kf1 {The safest square
for the king.} Nf5 36. Ng4 Qa6 37. Rc3 $1 {Blocking the c-pawn at the price of
a rook.} d4 38. hxg6 fxg6 39. Bxf5 dxc3 40. Qxc3 $18) (31. Qc2 $6 {is less
accurate than 31.Qd3:} Ng4+ $1 32. Nxg4 ({The point is that} 32. Kg2 $2 {
runs into} Ne3+) 32... Qxg4 {With his queen active Black is relatively safe.})
31... hxg4 32. h5 $1 gxh5 33. Qc2 (33. Nf1 {planning Rh1} h4 34. Qd3 {is
similar to the main line.}) 33... f5 $1 (33... Bg7 34. Qh7+ Kf8 35. f5 $18) 34.
exf6 Re4 $1 35. Nxe4 dxe4 36. Qc4+ $1 {The most precise check, dooming the
pawn on e4.} (36. Qb3+ $6 {was the game continuation, offering Black an
essential tempo.} Kh8 37. d5 Bb7 $1 (37... Qd7 38. Bxe4 $14 h4 $2 {Bukic,E 
(2480) -Ivanovic,B (2490) Borovo 1981 (0-1, 44)} 39. Nf3 $3 {Aiming at either
activating the knight or making the f3-square available for the king.} gxf3 40.
dxc6 Qd4+ 41. Kxf3 $1 $18 {The point. The king is safe and White has an extra
exchange and a decisive attack.}) 38. Qc4 h4 39. Nf1 Qd7 40. Ne3) 36... Kh8 (
36... Nf7 37. d5 Nd6 38. Qc3 Bxd5 39. Qe5 Qf5 40. Rcd1 Be6 41. Nf3 $1 $16 {
A beautiful way of using the pin of the black pawns.}) 37. d5 Qd7 38. Qxe4 {
This is the point behind Qc4+.} Bxd5 39. Qg6 $18 *

