{Black is well regrouped and the bishop on b1 is passive. But if White manages
to play Nd4 he would retain a solid position. Your move with black.} 22... Rxc1
$1 {It is essential to force White to weaken the control over d4.} (22... d4 $6
{is premature due to} 23. Nxd4 {threatening to take on e6 with a check.}) 23.
Nxc1 (23. Rxc1 {looks more natural but you will have the occasion to refute it
in the next test.}) 23... a5 {Forcing the queen on a passive and exposed
square.} (23... d4 24. exd4 a5 {transposes.}) 24. Qd2 d4 $1 (24... Qc6 $6 {
still offers White hopes to stay in the game:} 25. Ne2 d4 26. e4 $15) 25. exd4
(25. e4 {loses the pawn without compensation. The point is that despite his
excellent blocking knight, White remains very passive:} Bxe4 26. Bxe4 Rxe4 27.
Nd3 Re2 28. Qc1 Qa4 29. Qb1 h5 $5 $19) 25... Bg5 $1 {Forcing White to weaken
the e3-square and the second rank.} 26. f4 (26. Qc3 Rc6 {wins the knight.}) (
26. Qd3 Re1+ 27. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 28. Qf1 Qxf1+ 29. Kxf1 Bxc1 $19) 26... Bf6 {
Black is poorly coordinated and has many weaknesses. Black only needs to
retrieve the pawn to obtain a position with excellent winning chances.} 27. d5
(27. h3 Rd6 28. Qf2 Qa4 $17) 27... Bxd5 $17 28. Qxd5 $2 Re1+ {mates} *

